# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: european-union
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:european-union/12-number] Twelve is the 3rd superior highly composite number, the 3rd colossally abundant number, the 5th highly composite number, and is divisible by the numbers from 1 to 4, and 6, a comparatively large number of divisors.
[src:european-union/12-number] It is central to many systems of timekeeping, including the Western calendar and units of time of day, and frequently appears in the world's major religions.
[src:european-union/12-number] Twelve is the largest number with a single-syllable name in English.
[src:european-union/12-number] Such uses gradually disappeared with the introduction of Arabic numerals during the 12th-century Renaissance.
[src:european-union/12-number] Derived from Old English, **twelf** and **tuelf** are first attested in the 10th-century Lindisfarne Gospels' Book of John.
[src:european-union/12-number] It has cognates in every Germanic language (e.g.
[src:european-union/12-number] German *zwölf*), whose Proto-Germanic ancestor has been reconstructed as ***twaliƀi...**, from ***twa** ("two") and suffix ***-lif-** or ***-liƀ-** of uncertain meaning.
[src:european-union/12-number] It is sometimes compared with the Lithuanian **dvýlika**, although **-lika** is used as the suffix for all numbers from 11 to 19 (analogous to "-teen").
[src:european-union/12-number] Every other Indo-European language instead uses a form of "two"+"ten", such as the Latin **duōdecim**.
[src:european-union/12-number] The usual ordinal form is "twelfth" but "dozenth" or "duodecimal" (from the Latin word) is also used in some contexts, particularly base-12 numeration.
[src:european-union/12-number] Similarly, a group of twelve things is usually a "dozen" but may also be referred to as a "dodecad" or "duodecad".
[src:european-union/12-number] The adjective referring to a group of twelve is "duodecuple".
[src:european-union/12-number] As with eleven, the earliest forms of twelve are often considered to be connected with Proto-Germanic ***liƀan** or ***liƀan** ("to leave"), with the implicit meaning that "two is left" after having already counted to ten.
[src:european-union/12-number] The Lithuanian suffix is also considered to share a similar development.
[src:european-union/12-number] The suffix ***-lif-** has also been connected with reconstructions of the Proto-Germanic for ten.
[src:european-union/12-number] As mentioned above, 12 has its own name in Germanic languages such as English (dozen), Dutch (*dozijn*), German (*Dutzend*), and Swedish (*dussin*), all derived from Old French **dozaine**.
[src:european-union/12-number] It is a compound number in many other languages, e.g.
[src:european-union/12-number] Italian **dodici** (but in Spanish and Portuguese, 16, and in French, 17 is the first compound number), Japanese 十二 *jūni*.
[src:european-union/12-number] In prose writing, *twelve*, being the last single-syllable numeral, is sometimes taken as the last number to be written as a word, and 13 the first to be written using digits.
[src:european-union/12-number] This is not a binding rule, and in English language tradition, it is sometimes recommended to spell out numbers up to and including either *nine*, *ten* or *twelve*, or even *ninety-nine* or *one hundred*.
[src:european-union/12-number] Another system spells out all numbers written in one or two words (*sixteen*, *twenty-seven*, *fifteen thousand*, but *372* or *15,001*).
[src:european-union/12-number] In German orthography, there used to be the widely followed (but unofficial) rule of spelling out numbers up to twelve (*zwölf*).
[src:european-union/12-number] The Duden (the German standard dictionary) mentions this rule as outdated.
[src:european-union/12-number] There are twelve Jacobian elliptic functions and twelve cubic distance-transitive graphs.
[src:european-union/12-number] In its regular form, it is the largest polygon that can uniformly tile the plane alongside other regular polygons, as with the truncated hexagonal tiling or the truncated trihexagonal tiling.
[src:european-union/12-number] A regular dodecahedron has twelve pentagonal faces.
[src:european-union/12-number] Regular cubes and octahedrons both have 12 edges, while regular icosahedrons have 12 vertices.
[src:european-union/12-number] The cubic close packing and hexagonal close packing, which are the two densest possible sphere packings in three-dimensional space (the Kepler conjecture, proved by Thomas Hales), both have each sphere touching twelve other spheres.
[src:european-union/12-number] Twelve is also the kissing number in three dimensions.
[src:european-union/12-number] There are twelve complex apeirotopes in dimensions five and higher, which include van Oss polytopes in the form of complex n -orthoplexes.
[src:european-union/12-number] There are also twelve paracompact hyperbolic Coxeter groups of uniform polytopes in five-dimensional space.
[src:european-union/12-number] Bring's curve is a Riemann surface of genus four, with a domain that is a regular hyperbolic 20-sided icosagon.
[src:european-union/12-number] By the Gauss-Bonnet theorem, the area of this fundamental polygon is equal to $12\pi$ .
[src:european-union/12-number] Twelve is the smallest weight for which a cusp form exists.
[src:european-union/12-number] Although the series is divergent, methods such as Ramanujan summation can assign finite values to divergent series.
[src:european-union/12-number] The duodecimal system (1210 [twelve] = 1012), which is the use of 12 as a division factor for many ancient and medieval weights and measures, including hours, probably originates from Mesopotamia.
[src:european-union/12-number] The number twelve carries religious, mythological and magical symbolism; since antiquity, the number has generally represented perfection, entirety, or cosmic order.
[src:european-union/12-number] Ishmael—the first-born son of Abraham—has 12 sons/princes (Genesis 25:16), and Jacob also has 12 sons, who are the progenitors of the Twelve Tribes of Israel.
[src:european-union/12-number] This is reflected in Christian tradition, notably in the twelve Apostles.
[src:european-union/12-number] When Judas Iscariot is disgraced, a meeting is held (Acts) to add Saint Matthias to complete the number twelve once more.
[src:european-union/12-number] The Old Testament contains Twelve Minor Prophets.
[src:european-union/12-number] The Book of Revelation contains much numerical symbolism, and many of the numbers mentioned have 12 as a divisor.
[src:european-union/12-number] 12:1 mentions a woman—interpreted as the people of Israel, the Church and the Virgin Mary—wearing a crown of twelve stars (representing each of the twelve tribes of Israel).
[src:european-union/12-number] Furthermore, there are 12,000 people sealed from each of the twelve tribes of Israel (the Tribe of Dan is omitted while Manasseh is mentioned), making a total of 144,000 (which is the square of 12 multiplied by a thousand).
[src:european-union/12-number] There are considered to be 12 misls in the Sikh Conferacy.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The **14th Dalai Lama** (born **Lhamo Thondup**; 6 July 1935; full spiritual name: **Jetsun Jamphel Ngawang Lobsang Yeshe Tenzin Gyatso**, shortened as **Tenzin Gyatso**) is the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He served as the resident spiritual and temporal leader of Tibet before 1959, and subsequently led the Tibetan government in exile represented by the Central Tibetan Administration in Dharamshala, India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] A belief central to the Tibetan Buddhist tradition as well as the institution of the Dalai Lama is that the reincarnated person is a living Bodhisattva, specifically an emanation of Avalokiteśvara (in Sanskrit) or Chenrezig (in Tibetan), the Bodhisattva of Compassion.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Mongolic word *dalai* means *ocean.* The 14th Dalai Lama is also known to Tibetans as **Gyalwa Rinpoche** ("The Precious Jewel-like Buddha-Master"), *Kundun* ("The Presence"), and *Yizhin Norbu* ("The Wish-Fulfilling Gem").
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His devotees, as well as much of the Western world, often call him ***His Holiness the Dalai Lama***.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He is the leader and a monk of the newest Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama was born to a farming family in Taktser (*Hongya* village), in the traditional Tibetan region of Amdo, at the time a Chinese frontier district.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was selected as the tulku of the 13th Dalai Lama in 1937, and formally recognised as the 14th Dalai Lama in 1939.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As with the recognition process for his predecessor, a Golden Urn selection process was waived and approved by the Nationalist government of China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His enthronement ceremony was held in Lhasa on 22 February 1940.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following the Battle of Chamdo, in which PRC forces annexed Central Tibet, the Tibetan government, the Ganden Phodrang, invested the Dalai Lama with temporal duties on 17 November 1950 (at 15 years of age), which he held until his exile in 1959.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] During the 1959 Tibetan uprising, the Dalai Lama escaped to India, where he continues to live.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 29 April 1959, the Dalai Lama established the independent Tibetan government in exile in the north Indian hill station of Mussoorie, which then moved in May 1960 to Dharamshala, where he resides.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He retired as political head in 2011 to make way for a democratic government, the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama advocates for the welfare of Tibetans and since the early 1970s has called for the Middle Way Approach with China to peacefully resolve the issue of Tibet.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He criticised the CIA Tibetan program, saying that its sudden end in 1972 proved it was primarily aimed at serving American interests.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Up until his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama travelled worldwide to give Tibetan Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism teachings, and his Kalachakra teachings and initiations were international events.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He also attended conferences on a wide range of subjects, including the relationship between religion and science, met with other world leaders, religious leaders, philosophers, and scientists, online and in-person.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Since 2018, he has continued to teach on a reduced schedule, limiting his travel to within India only, and occasionally addressing international audiences via live webcasts.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His work includes focus on the environment, economics, women's rights, nonviolence, interfaith dialogue, physics, astronomy, Buddhism and science, cognitive neuroscience, reproductive health and sexuality.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] *Time* magazine named the Dalai Lama Gandhi's spiritual heir to nonviolence.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In addition, an Indian MP delegation led by Sujeet Kumar, Member of Parliament, Rajya Sabha has advocated for the Dalai Lama to receive the Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour in India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Lhamo Thondup was born on 6 July 1935, to Choekyong Tsering and his wife Dekyi Tsering, a farming and horse trading family in the small hamlet of Taktser under the control of the Ma clique loyal to the Republic of China as part of Qinghai and on the edge of the traditionally Tibetan region of Amdo.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was one of seven siblings to survive childhood and one of the three supposed reincarnated Rinpoches in the same family.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest sister, Tsering Dolma, was 16 years his senior and was midwife to his mother at his birth.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] She would accompany him into exile and found Tibetan Children's Villages.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest brother, Thupten Jigme Norbu, had been recognised at the age of three by the 13th Dalai Lama as the reincarnation of the high Lama, the 6th Taktser Rinpoche.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His fifth brother, Tendzin Choegyal, had been recognised as the 16th Ngari Rinpoche.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His sister, Jetsun Pema, spent most of her adult life on the Tibetan Children's Villages project.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama has said that his first language was "a broken Xining language which was (a dialect of) the Chinese language, a form of Central Plains Mandarin", and his family speaks neither Amdo Tibetan nor Lhasa Tibetan.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] After the demise of the 13th Dalai Lama, in 1935, the Ordinance of Lama Temple Management was published by the Central Government.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1936, the Method of Reincarnation of Lamas was published by the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission of the Central Government.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 3 states that death of lamas, including the Dalai Lama and Panchen Lama, should be reported to the commission, soul boys should be located and checked by the commission, and a lot-drawing ceremony with the Golden Urn system should be held.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 6 states that local governments should invite officials from the Central Government to take care of the sitting-in-the-bed ceremony.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 7 states that soul boys should not be sought from current lama families.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This article echoes what the Qianlong Emperor described in The Discourse of Lama to eliminate greedy families with multiple reincarnated rinpoches, lamas.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Based on custom and regulation, the regent was actively involved in the search for the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following reported signs and visions, three search teams were sent out to the north-east, the east, and the south-east to locate the new incarnation when the boy who was to become the 14th Dalai Lama was about two years old.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Sir Basil Gould, British delegate to Lhasa in 1936, related his account of the north-eastern team to Sir Charles Alfred Bell, former British resident in Lhasa and friend of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Among other omens, the head of the embalmed body of the 13th Dalai Lama, at first facing south-east, had turned to face the north-east, indicating, it was interpreted, the direction in which his successor would be found.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Regent, Reting Rinpoche, shortly afterwards had a vision at the sacred lake of Lhamo La-tso which he interpreted as Amdo being the region to search.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This vision was also interpreted to refer to a large monastery with a gilded roof and turquoise tiles, and a twisting path from there to a hill to the east, opposite which stood a small house with distinctive eaves.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The team, led by Kewtsang Rinpoche, went first to meet the Panchen Lama, who had been stuck in Jyekundo, in northern Kham.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Panchen Lama had been investigating births of unusual children in the area ever since the death of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He gave Kewtsang the names of three boys whom he had discovered and identified as candidates.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Within a year the Panchen Lama had died.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two of his three candidates were crossed off the list but the third, a "fearless" child, the most promising, was from Taktser village, which, as in the vision, was on a hill, at the end of a trail leading to Taktser from the great Kumbum Monastery with its gilded, turquoise roof.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] There they found a house, as interpreted from the vision—the house where Lhamo Dhondup lived.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama claims that at the time, the village of Taktser stood right on the "real border" between the region of Amdo and China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the search lore, when the team visited, posing as pilgrims, its leader, a Sera Lama, pretended to be the servant and sat separately in the kitchen.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He held an old mala that had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama, and the boy Lhamo Dhondup, aged two, approached and asked for it.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The monk said, "If you know who I am, you can have it." The child said, "Sera Lama, Sera Lama", and spoke with him in a Lhasa accent, in a dialect the boy's mother could not understand.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The next time the party returned to the house, they revealed their real purpose and asked permission to subject the boy to certain tests.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] One test consisted of showing him various pairs of objects, one of which had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama and one which had not.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In every case, he chose the Dalai Lama's own objects and rejected the others.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] From 1936 the Hui "Ma clique" Muslim warlord Ma Bufang ruled Qinghai as its governor under the nominal authority of the Republic of China central government.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to an interview with the 14th Dalai Lama, in the 1930s, Ma Bufang had seized this north-east corner of Amdo in the name of Chiang Kai-shek's weak government and incorporated it into the Chinese province of Qinghai.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Before going to Taktser, Kewtsang had gone to Ma Bufang to pay his respects.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] When Ma Bufang heard a candidate had been found in Taktser, he had the family brought to him in Xining.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He first demanded proof that the boy was the Dalai Lama, but the Lhasa government, though informed by Kewtsang that this was the one, told Kewtsang to say he had to go to Lhasa for further tests with other candidates.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They knew that if he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, the Chinese government would insist on sending a large army escort with him, which would then stay in Lhasa and refuse to budge.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Ma Bufang, together with Kumbum Monastery, then refused to allow him to depart unless he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, but withdrew this demand in return for 100,000 Chinese dollars ransom in silver to be shared among them, to let them go to Lhasa.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two years of diplomatic wrangling followed before it was accepted by Lhasa that the ransom had to be paid to avoid the Chinese getting involved and escorting him to Lhasa with a large army.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Meanwhile, the boy was kept at Kumbum where two of his brothers were already studying as monks and recognised incarnate lamas.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The payment of 300,000 silver dollars was then advanced by Muslim traders en route to Mecca in a large caravan via Lhasa.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They paid Ma Bufang on behalf of the Tibetan government against promissory notes to be redeemed, with interest, in Lhasa.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 20,000-dollar fee for an escort was dropped, since the Muslim merchants invited them to join their caravan for protection; Ma Bufang sent 20 of his soldiers with them and was paid from both sides since the Chinese government granted him another 50,000 dollars for the expenses of the journey.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Furthermore, the Indian government helped the Tibetans raise the ransom funds by affording them import concessions.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 22 September 1938, representatives of Tibet Office in Beijing informed Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that 3 candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held in Tibet.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In October 1938, the Method of Using Golden Urn for the 14th Dalai Lama was drafted by Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 12 December 1938, regent Jamphel Yeshe Gyaltsen, the serving Reting Rinpoche, informed the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that three candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Released from Kumbum, on 21 July 1939 the party travelled across Tibet on a journey to Lhasa in the large Muslim caravan with Lhamo Dhondup, now four years old, riding with his brother Lobsang in a special palanquin carried by two mules, two years after being discovered.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As soon as they were out of Ma Bufang's area, he was officially declared to be the 14th Dalai Lama by the Kashag, and after ten weeks of travel he arrived in Lhasa on 8 October 1939.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The ordination (pabbajja) and giving of the monastic name of Tenzin Gyatso were arranged by Reting Rinpoche and according to the Dalai Lama "I received my ordination from Kyabjé Ling Rinpoché in the Jokhang in Lhasa." There was very limited Chinese involvement at this time.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The family of the 14th Dalai Lama was elevated to the highest stratum of the Tibetan aristocracy and acquired land and serf holdings, as with the families of previous Dalai Lamas.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1959, at the age of 23, he took his final examination at Lhasa's Jokhang Temple during the annual Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He passed with honours and was awarded the Lharampa degree, the highest-level *geshe* degree, roughly equivalent to a doctorate in Buddhist philosophy.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, he had a succession of tutors in Tibet including Reting Rinpoche, Tathag Rinpoche, Ling Rinpoche and lastly Trijang Rinpoche, who became junior tutor when he was 19.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] At the age of 11 he met the Austrian mountaineer Heinrich Harrer, who became his videographer and tutor about the world outside Lhasa.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The two remained friends until Harrer's death in 2006.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Historically the Dalai Lamas or their regents held political and religious leadership over Tibet from Lhasa with varying degrees of influence depending on the regions of Tibet and periods of history.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This began with the 5th Dalai Lama's rule in 1642 and lasted until the 1950s (except for 1705–1750), during which period the Dalai Lamas headed the Tibetan government or Ganden Phodrang.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until 1912 however, when the 13th Dalai Lama declared the complete independence of Tibet, their rule was generally subject to patronage and protection of firstly Mongol kings (1642–1720) and then the Manchu-led Qing dynasty (1720–1912).
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterwards in 1939, at the age of four, the Dalai Lama was taken in a procession of lamas to Lhasa.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Former British officials stationed in India and Tibet recalled that envoys from Britain and China were present at the Dalai Lama's enthronement in February 1940.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] According to Basil Gould, the Chinese representative Wu Chunghsin was reportedly unhappy about the position he had during the ceremony.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterward an article appeared in the Chinese press falsely claiming that Wu personally announced the installation of the Dalai Lama, who supposedly prostrated himself to Wu in gratitude.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After his enthronement, the Dalai Lama's childhood was then spent between the Potala Palace and Norbulingka, his summer residence, both of which are now UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang Kai Shek ordered Ma Bufang to put his Muslim soldiers on alert for an invasion of Tibet in 1942.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang complied, and moved several thousand troops to the border with Tibet.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang also threatened the Tibetans with aerial bombardment if they worked with the Japanese.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang attacked the Tibetan Buddhist Tsang monastery in 1941.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He also constantly attacked the Labrang monastery.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 1950 the army of the People's Republic of China marched to the edge of the Dalai Lama's territory and sent a delegation after defeating a legion of the Tibetan army in warlord-controlled Kham.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 17 November 1950, at the age of 15, the 14th Dalai Lama assumed full temporal (political) power as ruler of Tibet.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's formal rule as head of the government in Tibet was brief although he was enthroned as spiritual leader on 22 February 1940.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When Chinese cadres entered Tibet in 1950, with a crisis looming, the Dalai Lama was asked to assume the role of head of state at the age of 15, which he did on 17 November 1950.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Customarily the Dalai Lama would typically assume control at about the age of 20.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He sent a delegation to Beijing, which signed the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama believes the draft agreement was written by China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Tibetan representatives were not allowed to suggest any alterations and China did not allow the Tibetan representatives to communicate with the Tibetan government in Lhasa.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan delegation was not authorised by Lhasa to sign, but ultimately submitted to pressure from the Chinese to sign anyway, using seals specifically made for the purpose.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Seventeen Point Agreement recognised Chinese sovereignty over Tibet, but China allowed the Dalai Lama to continue to rule Tibet internally, and it allowed the system of feudal peasantry to persist.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1951, following a lengthy discussion with the returning delegates, the National Assembly recommended that the Dalai Lama accept the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He telegraphed his confirmation to Chairman Mao Zedong on 24 October.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scholar Robert Barnett wrote of the serfdom controversy: "So even if it were agreed that serfdom and feudalism existed in Tibet, this would be little different other than in technicalities from conditions in any other 'premodern' peasant society, including most of China at that time.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The power of the Chinese argument therefore lies in its implication that serfdom, and with it feudalism, is inseparable from extreme abuse.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Evidence to support this linkage has not been found by scholars other than those close to Chinese governmental circles.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The 19-year-old Dalai Lama toured China for almost a year from 1954 to 1955, meeting many of the revolutionary leaders and the top echelon of the Chinese communist leadership who created modern China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He learned Chinese and socialist ideals, as explained by his Chinese hosts, on a tour of China showcasing the benefits of socialism and the effective governance provided to turn the large, impoverished nation into a modern and egalitarian society, which impressed him.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1954, he went to the Chinese capital to meet Chairman Mao Zedong with the 10th Panchen Lama and attend the 1st National People's Congress as a delegate, primarily discussing China's constitution.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 27 September 1954, the Dalai Lama was selected as a Vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, a post he officially held until 1964.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1956, on a trip to India to celebrate the Buddha's Birthday, the Dalai Lama asked the Prime Minister of India, Jawaharlal Nehru, if he would allow him political asylum should he choose to stay.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Nehru discouraged this as a provocation against peace, and reminded him of the Indian Government's non-interventionist stance agreed upon with its 1954 treaty with China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Long called a "splittist" and "traitor" by China, the Dalai Lama has attempted formal talks over Tibet's status in China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Chinese Foreign Ministry has warned the US and other countries to "shun" the Dalai Lama during visits and often uses trade negotiations and human rights talks as an incentive to do so.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] China sporadically bans images of the Dalai Lama and arrests citizens for owning photos of him in Tibet.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In April 2018, the Dalai Lama confirmed Chinese government claims about Gedhun Choekyi Nyima by saying that he knew from "reliable sources" that the Panchen Lama he had recognised was alive and receiving normal education.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He said he hoped that the Chinese-recognised Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is a target of Chinese state sponsored hacking.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Security experts claim "targeting Tibetan activists is a strong indicator of official Chinese government involvement" since economic information is the primary goal of private Chinese hackers.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009 the personal office of the Dalai Lama asked researchers at the Munk Center for International Studies at the University of Toronto to check its computers for malicious software.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] A second cyberspy network, Shadow Network, was discovered by the same researchers in 2010.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Stolen documents included a year's worth of the Dalai Lama's personal email, and classified government material relating to India, West Africa, the Russian Federation, the Middle East, and NATO.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] "Sophisticated" hackers were linked to universities in China, Beijing again denied involvement.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chinese hackers posing as The New York Times, Amnesty International and other organisation's reporters targeted the private office of the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Parliament members, and Tibetan nongovernmental organisations, among others, in 2019.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the outset of the 1959 Tibetan uprising, fearing for his life, the Dalai Lama and his retinue fled Tibet with the help of the CIA's Special Activities Division, crossing into India on 30 March 1959, reaching Tezpur in Assam on 18 April.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Some time later he set up the Government of Tibet in Exile in Dharamshala, India, which is often referred to as "*Little Lhasa*".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After the founding of the government in exile he re-established the approximately 80,000 Tibetan refugees who followed him into exile in agricultural settlements.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He created a Tibetan educational system in order to teach the Tibetan children the language, history, religion, and culture.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan Institute of Performing Arts was established in 1959 and the Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies became the primary university for Tibetans in India in 1967.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He supported the refounding of 200 monasteries and nunneries in an attempt to preserve Tibetan Buddhist teachings and the Tibetan way of life.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama appealed to the United Nations on the rights of Tibetans.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This appeal resulted in three resolutions adopted by the General Assembly in 1959, 1961, and 1965, all before the People's Republic was allowed representation at the United Nations.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The resolutions called on China to respect the human rights of Tibetans.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1963, he promulgated a democratic constitution which is based upon the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, creating an elected parliament and an administration to champion his cause.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1970, he opened the Library of Tibetan Works and Archives in Dharamshala which houses over 80,000 manuscripts and important knowledge resources related to Tibetan history, politics and culture.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] It is considered one of the most important institutions for Tibetology in the world.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2016, there were demands from Indian citizens and politicians of different political parties to confer the Dalai Lama the prestigious Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour of India, which has only been awarded to a non-Indian citizen twice in its history.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2021, it was revealed that the Dalai Lama's inner circle were listed in the Pegasus project data as having been targeted with spyware on their phones.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Analysis strongly indicates potential targets were selected by the Indian government.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2025, Indian Members of Parliament (MPs), led by Sujeet Kumar, BJP Rajya Sabha MP, called for His Holiness to be awarded the Bharat Ratna.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the Congressional Human Rights Caucus in 1987 in Washington, D.C., the Dalai Lama gave a speech outlining his ideas for the future status of Tibet.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan called for Tibet to become a democratic "zone of peace" without nuclear weapons, and with support for human rights.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan would come to be known as the "Strasbourg proposal", because the Dalai Lama expanded on the plan at Strasbourg on 15 June 1988.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] There, he proposed the creation of a self-governing Tibet "in association with the People's Republic of China." This would have been pursued by negotiations with the PRC government, but the plan was rejected by the Tibetan Government-in-Exile in 1991.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has indicated that he wishes to return to Tibet only if the People's Republic of China agrees not to make any precondition for his return.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In the 1970s, the Paramount leader Deng Xiaoping set China's sole return requirement to the Dalai Lama as that he "must [come back] as a Chinese citizen ... that is, patriotism".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama celebrated his 70th birthday on 6 July 2005.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] About 10,000 Tibetan refugees, monks and foreign tourists gathered outside his home.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Patriarch Alexius II of the Russian Orthodox Church alleged positive relations with Buddhists.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] However, later that year, the Russian state prevented the Dalai Lama from fulfilling an invitation to the traditionally Buddhist republic of Kalmykia.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The President of the Republic of China (Taiwan), Chen Shui-bian, attended an evening celebrating the Dalai Lama's birthday at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall in Taipei.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 2008 in Japan, the Dalai Lama addressed the 2008 Tibetan violence that had erupted and that the Chinese government accused him of fomenting.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He responded that he had "lost faith" in efforts to negotiate with the Chinese government, and that it was "up to the Tibetan people" to decide what to do.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] During his visit to Taiwan after Typhoon Morakot 30 Taiwanese indigenous peoples protested against the Dalai Lama and denounced it as politically motivated.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is an advocate for a world free of nuclear weapons, and serves on the Advisory Council of the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has voiced his support for the Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly, an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until reaching his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama maintained a busy international lecture and teaching schedule.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, he has continued to teach, but has limited his travel to within India only.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] His public talks and teachings are usually webcast live in multiple languages, via an inviting organisation's website, or on the Dalai Lama's own website.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scores of his past teaching videos can be viewed there, as well as public talks, conferences, interviews, dialogues and panel discussions.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's best known teaching subject is the Kalachakra tantra which, as of 2014, he had conferred a total of 33 times, most often in India's upper Himalayan regions but also in the Western world.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) is one of the most complex teachings of Buddhism, sometimes taking two weeks to confer, and he often confers it on very large audiences, up to 200,000 students and disciples at a time.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is the author of numerous books on Buddhism, many of them on general Buddhist subjects but also including books on particular topics like Dzogchen, a Nyingma practice.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, his schedule has contained fewer engagements, with most occurring in India along with a handful webcasts to international audiences.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Again in London in 1996 he taught the Four Noble Truths, the basis and foundation of Buddhism accepted by all Buddhists, at the combined invitation of 27 different Buddhist organisations of all schools and traditions belonging to the Network of Buddhist Organisations UK.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In India, no fees are charged to attend these teachings since costs are covered by requesting sponsors.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When he travels abroad to give teachings there is usually a ticket fee calculated by the inviting organisation to cover the costs involved and any surplus is normally to be donated to recognised charities.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has frequently visited and lectured at colleges and universities, some of which have conferred honorary degrees upon him.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Dozens of videos of recorded webcasts of the Dalai Lama's public talks on general subjects for non-Buddhists like peace, happiness and compassion, modern ethics, the environment, economic and social issues, gender, the empowerment of women and so forth can be viewed in his office's archive.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama met Pope Paul VI at the Vatican in 1973.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1990, he met a delegation of Jewish teachers in Dharamshala for an extensive interfaith dialogue.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has since visited Israel three times, and in 2006 met the Chief Rabbi of Israel.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2006, he met Pope Benedict XVI privately.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has met the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Robert Runcie, and other leaders of the Anglican Church in London, Gordon B.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Hinckley, who at the time was the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as well as senior Eastern Orthodox Church, Muslim, Hindu, Jewish, and Sikh officials.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1996 and 2002, he participated in the first two Gethsemani Encounters hosted by the Monastic Interreligious Dialogue at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani, where Thomas Merton, whom the Dalai Lama had met in the late 1960s, had lived.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He is also a member of the Board of World Religious Leaders as part of The Elijah Interfaith Institute and participated in the Third Meeting of the Board of World Religious Leaders in Amritsar, India, on 26 November 2007 to discuss the topic of Love and Forgiveness.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009, the Dalai Lama inaugurated an interfaith "World Religions-Dialogue and Symphony" conference at Gujarat's Mahuva religions, according to Morari Bapu.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2010, the Dalai Lama, joined by a panel of scholars, launched the Common Ground Project, in Bloomington, Indiana (USA), which was planned by himself and Prince Ghazi bin Muhammad of Jordan during several years of personal conversations.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The project is based on the book *Common Ground between Islam and Buddhism*.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2019, the Dalai Lama fully sponsored the first-ever 'Celebrating Diversity in the Muslim World' conference in New Delhi on behalf of the Muslims of Ladakh.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's lifelong interest in science and technology dates from his childhood in Lhasa, Tibet, when he was fascinated by mechanical objects like clocks, watches, telescopes, film projectors, clockwork soldiers and motor cars, and loved to repair, disassemble and reassemble them.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Once, observing the Moon through a telescope as a child, he realised it was a crater-pocked lump of rock and not a heavenly body emitting its own light as Tibetan cosmologists had taught him.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has also said that had he not been brought up as a monk he would probably have been an engineer.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On his first trip to the west in 1973 he asked to visit Cambridge University's astrophysics department in the UK and he sought out renowned scientists such as Sir Karl Popper, David Bohm and Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, who taught him the basics of science.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama sees important common ground between science and Buddhism in having the same approach to challenge dogma on the basis of empirical evidence that comes from observation and analysis of phenomena.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Also in 1983, the American social entrepreneur and innovator R.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Adam Engle, who had become aware of the Dalai Lama's deep interest in science, was already considering the idea of facilitating for him a serious dialogue with a selection of appropriate scientists.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1984 Engle formally offered to the Dalai Lama's office to organise a week-long, formal dialogue for him with a suitable team of scientists, provided that the Dalai Lama would wish to fully participate in such a dialogue.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Within 48 hours the Dalai Lama confirmed to Engle that he was "truly interested in participating in something substantial about science" so Engle proceeded with launching the project.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Francisco Varela, having heard about Engle's proposal, then called him to tell him of his earlier discussions with the Dalai Lama and to offer his scientific collaboration to the project.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Engle accepted, and Varela assisted him to assemble his team of six specialist scientists for the first 'Mind and Life' dialogue on the cognitive sciences, which was eventually held with the Dalai Lama at his residence in Dharamsala in 1987.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This five-day event was so successful that at the end the Dalai Lama told Engle he would very much like to repeat it again in the future.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As Mind and Life Institute's remit expanded, Engle formalised the organisation as a non-profit foundation after the third dialogue, held in 1990, which initiated the undertaking of neurobiological research programmes in the United States under scientific conditions.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Sponsors and partners in these dialogues have included the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Johns Hopkins University, the Mayo Clinic, and Zurich University.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Apart from time spent teaching Buddhism and fulfilling responsibilities to his Tibetan followers, the Dalai Lama spends time and resources investigating the interface between Buddhism and science through the ongoing series of Mind and Life dialogues and its spin-offs.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As the institute's Cofounder and the Honorary chairman he has personally presided over and participated in all its dialogues, which continue to expand worldwide.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have given rise to dozens of DVD sets of the dialogues and books he has authored on them such as *Ethics for the New Millennium* and *The Universe in a Single Atom*, as well as scientific papers and university research programmes.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On the Tibetan and Buddhist side, science subjects have been added to the curriculum for Tibetan monastic educational institutions and scholarship.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] SEE learning focuses on developing critical thinking, ethical reasoning and compassion and stresses on commonalities rather than on the differences.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In particular, the Mind and Life Education Humanities & Social Sciences initiatives have been instrumental in developing the emerging field of Contemplative Science, by researching, for example, the effects of contemplative practice on the human brain, behaviour and biology.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have even had an impact in the Chinese capital.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2013 an 'academic dialogue' with a Chinese scientist, a Tibetan 'living Buddha' and a professor of Religion took place in Beijing.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Entitled "High-end dialogue: ancient Buddhism and modern science" it addressed the same considerations that interest the Dalai Lama, described as 'discussing about the similarities between Buddhism and modern science'.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama uses various meditation techniques, including analytic meditation and emptiness meditation.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2007, the 14th Dalai Lama said his reincarnation could be a woman.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This was mentioned again in 2015 and 2019.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In May 2011, the Dalai Lama retired from the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2011, the Dalai Lama repeated his statement in an interview with Canadian CTV News.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He added that Chinese laws banning the selection of successors based on reincarnation will not impact his decisions.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "Naturally my next life is entirely up to me.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And also this is not a political matter", he said in the interview.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama also added that he has not decided on whether he would reincarnate or be the last Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview with the German newspaper *Welt am Sonntag* published on 7 September 2014 the Dalai Lama stated "the institution of the Dalai Lama has served its purpose", and that "We had a Dalai Lama for almost five centuries.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The 14th Dalai Lama now is very popular.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Let us then finish with a popular Dalai Lama." In response, the Chinese government said the title of Dalai Lama has been conferred by the central government for hundreds of years and the 14th Dalai Lama has ulterior motives.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This was taken by Tibetan activists and *The Wire* to mean that China will make the Dalai Lama reincarnate no matter what.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Gyatso has also expressed fear that the Chinese government would manipulate any reincarnation selection in order to choose a successor that would go along with their political goals.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015, the 14th Dalai Lama has claimed he may be reincarnated as a mischievous blonde woman.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama said that if a female Dalai Lama comes, she should be more attractive.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Chinese politician Padma Choling accused the 14th Dalai Lama of flip-flopping with his various statements on the issue, and of hypocrisy as he himself was reincarnated.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also accused the 14th Dalai Lama of profaning Tibetan Buddhism "by doubting his reincarnation".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama stated that because of the feudal origin of the Dalai Lama reincarnation system, the reincarnation system should end.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, in July 2025, as the 14th Dalai Lama reached the age of 90, he addressed growing discussions about his succession by reaffirming that he will be reincarnated and that the process of identifying his successor should follow traditional Tibetan Buddhist practices.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a message shared during a prayer ceremony and posted on social media, the Dalai Lama stated that only his non-profit institution, Gaden Phodrang Foundation of the Dalai Lama, has the legitimate authority to oversee the selection of his reincarnation.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised that the identification of the 15th Dalai Lama should involve consultation with senior leaders of Tibetan Buddhist schools and with spiritual entities known as oath-bound Dharma Protectors, following established historical customs.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama reaffirmed that his reincarnation will occur outside China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a direct challenge to China, he asserted that the centuries-old spiritual institution bearing his name will endure beyond his death, emphasising that only his inner circle—not Beijing—will have the authority to identify his successor.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has stated that his successor will be born in a free country, suggesting that the next reincarnation could come from the Tibetan diaspora—around 140,000 people worldwide, with about half residing in India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In response, the Chinese government rejected the Dalai Lama's position.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Officials in Beijing stated that the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama, as well as other high-ranking Tibetan Buddhist figures such as the Panchen Lama, must be approved by the central government.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the government holds ultimate authority in confirming the identity of reincarnated Tibetan spiritual leaders.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Samdhong Rinpoche Lobsang Tenzin, a senior leader of the Dalai Lama's trust, affirmed the continuation of the Dalai Lama institution, stating that both a 15th and 16th Dalai Lama would follow.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said the current Dalai Lama would issue guidelines for identifying his successor.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Deputy speaker of the parliament of the Central Tibetan Administration Dolma Tsering Teykhang accused China of trying to control the reincarnation process and emphasised the need for the Dalai Lama to address the world directly.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his book, *Voice for the Voiceless*, published in 2025, the 14th Dalai Lama said Tibetans worldwide want the institution of the Dalai Lama to continue after his death and specified that his successor would be born in the "free world".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Despite initially advocating for Tibetan independence from 1961 to 1974, the Dalai Lama no longer supports it.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Instead he advocates for more meaningful autonomy for Tibetans within the People's Republic of China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This approach is known as the "Middle Way".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2005, the 14th Dalai Lama emphasised that Tibet is a part of China, and Tibetan culture and Buddhism are part of Chinese culture.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a speech at Kolkata in 2017, the Dalai Lama stated that Tibetans wanted to stay with China and they did not desire independence.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said that he believed that China after opening up, had changed 40 to 50 per cent of what it was earlier, and that Tibetans wanted to get more development from China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2020, the Dalai Lama stated that he did not support Tibetan independence and hoped to visit China as a Nobel Prize winner.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said "I prefer the concept of a 'republic' in the People's Republic of China.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama maintains close ties with India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2008, the Dalai Lama said that Arunachal Pradesh, partially claimed by China, is part of India, citing the disputed 1914 Simla Accord.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dhundup Gyalpo, the Dalai Lama's eventual secretary in New Delhi, argued that Tibetan and Chinese peoples have no connections apart from a few culinary dishes and that Chinese Buddhists could also be deemed "Indian in spirituality", because both Tibetan and Chinese Buddhism originated from India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has said that, from the perspective of the Buddhist precepts, abortion is an act of killing.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, he clarified a more nuanced position, stating, "... it depends on the circumstances.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If the unborn child will be retarded or if the birth will create serious problems for the parent, these are cases where there can be an exception.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed his opposition to the death penalty, saying that it contradicts the Buddhist philosophy of non-violence and that it expresses anger, not compassion.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] During a 2005 visit to Japan, a country which has the death penalty, the Dalai Lama called for the abolition of the death penalty and said in his address, "Criminals, people who commit crimes, usually society rejects these people.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Give them some form of punishment to say they were wrong, but show them they are part of society and can change.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Show them compassion." The Dalai Lama has also praised US states that have abolished the death penalty.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama says that he is active in spreading India's message of nonviolence and religious harmony throughout the world.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "I am the messenger of India's ancient thoughts the world over." He has said that democracy has deep roots in India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He says he considers India the master and Tibet its disciple, as great scholars went from India to Tibet to teach Buddhism.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has noted that millions of people lost their lives in violence and the economies of many countries were ruined due to conflicts in the 20th century.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has also critiqued proselytisation and certain types of conversion, believing the practices to be contrary to the fundamental ideas of religious harmony and spiritual practice.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has stated that "It's very important that our religious traditions live in harmony with one another and I don't think proselytizing contributes to this.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, the Dalai Lama attended the World Conference on Human Rights and made a speech titled "Human Rights and Universal Responsibility".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2001, in response to a question from a Seattle schoolgirl, the Dalai Lama said that it is permissible to shoot someone in self-defence (if the person was "trying to kill you") and he emphasised that the shot should not be fatal.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2013, the Dalai Lama criticised Buddhist monks' attacks on Muslims in Myanmar and rejected violence by Buddhists, saying: "Buddha always teaches us about forgiveness, tolerance, compassion.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If from one corner of your mind, some emotion makes you want to hit, or want to kill, then please remember Buddha's faith. ...
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] All problems must be solved through dialogue, through talk.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has consistently praised India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In December 2018, he said Muslim countries like Bangladesh, Pakistan and Syria should learn about religion from India for peace in the world.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked in 2019 about attacks on the minority community in India including a recent one against a Muslim family in Gurgaon, he said: "There are always a few mischievous people, but that does not mean it a symbol of that nation".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reiterated in December 2021 that he thought India was a role model for religious harmony in the world.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama advocates compassion for animals and frequently urges people to try vegetarianism or at least reduce their consumption of meat.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In Tibet, where historically meat was the most common food, most monks historically have been omnivores, including the Dalai Lamas.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Fourteenth Dalai Lama was raised in a meat-eating family but converted to vegetarianism after arriving in India, where vegetables are much more easily available and vegetarianism is widespread.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He spent many years as a vegetarian, but after contracting hepatitis in India and suffering from weakness, his doctors told him to return to eating meat which he now does twice a week.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This attracted public attention when, during a visit to the White House, he was offered a vegetarian menu but declined by replying, as he is known to do on occasion when dining in the company of non-vegetarians, "I'm a Tibetan monk, not a vegetarian".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His own home kitchen, however, is completely vegetarian.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, the English singer Paul McCartney wrote a letter to the Dalai Lama inquiring why he was not a vegetarian.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] As McCartney later told *The Guardian*, "He wrote back very kindly, saying, 'my doctors tell me that I must eat meat'.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And I wrote back again, saying, you know, I don't think that's right. [...] I think now he's vegetarian most of the time.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] I think he's now being told, the more he meets doctors from the west, that he can get his protein somewhere else. [...] It just doesn't seem right – the Dalai Lama, on the one hand, saying, 'Hey guys, don't harm sentient beings...
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has referred to himself as a Marxist and has articulated criticisms of capitalism.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reports hearing of communism when he was very young, but only in the context of the destruction of the Mongolian People's Republic.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] It was only when he went on his trip to Beijing that he learned about Marxist theory from his interpreter Baba Phuntsog Wangyal of the Tibetan Communist Party.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At that time, he reports, "I was so attracted to Marxism, I even expressed my wish to become a Communist Party member", citing his favourite concepts of self-sufficiency and equal distribution of wealth.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He does not believe that China implemented "true Marxist policy", and thinks the historical communist states such as the Soviet Union "were far more concerned with their narrow national interests than with the Workers' International".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Moreover, he believes one flaw of historically "Marxist regimes" is that they place too much emphasis on destroying the ruling class, and not enough on compassion.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He finds Marxism superior to capitalism, believing the latter is only concerned with "how to make profits", whereas the former has "moral ethics".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] On India–Pakistan relations, the Dalai Lama in October 2019 said: "There is a difference between Indian and Pakistani Prime Minister's speech at the UN.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Indian Prime Minister talks about peace, and you know what his Pakistan counterpart said, getting China's political support is Pakistan's compulsion.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Pakistani leaders should calm down and think beyond emotions and should follow a realistic approach".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama is outspoken in his concerns about environmental problems, frequently giving public talks on themes related to the environment.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has pointed out that many rivers in Asia originate in Tibet, and that the melting of Himalayan glaciers could affect the countries in which the rivers flow.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He acknowledged official Chinese laws against deforestation in Tibet, but lamented they can be ignored due to possible corruption.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He was quoted as saying "ecology should be part of our daily life"; personally, he takes showers instead of baths, and turns lights off when he leaves a room.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Around 2005, he started campaigning for wildlife conservation, including by issuing a religious ruling against wearing tiger and leopard skins as garments.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama supports the anti-whaling position in the whaling controversy, but has criticised the activities of groups such as the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society (which carries out acts of what it calls aggressive nonviolence against property).
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Before the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference, he urged national leaders to put aside domestic concerns and take collective action against climate change.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's stances on topics of sexuality have changed over time.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A monk since childhood, the Dalai Lama has said that sex offers fleeting satisfaction and leads to trouble later, while chastity offers a better life and "more independence, more freedom".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has said that problems arising from conjugal life sometimes even lead to suicide or murder.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has asserted that all religions have the same view about adultery.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also says that in modern times all common, consensual sexual practices that do not cause harm to others are ethically acceptable and that society should accept and respect people who are gay or transgender from a secular point of view.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his 1996 book *Beyond Dogma*, he described a traditional Buddhist definition of an appropriate sexual act as follows: "A sexual act is deemed proper when the couples use the organs intended for sexual intercourse and nothing else ...
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Homosexuality, whether it is between men or between women, is not improper in itself.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] What is improper is the use of organs already defined as inappropriate for sexual contact." He elaborated in 1997, conceding that the basis of that teaching was unknown to him.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also conveyed his own "willingness to consider the possibility that some of the teachings may be specific to a particular cultural and historic context".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, the Dalai Lama has expressed concern at "reports of violence and discrimination against" LGBT people and urged "respect, tolerance and the full recognition of human rights for all".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2014 interview with Larry King, the Dalai Lama expressed that same-sex marriage is a personal issue, can be ethically socially accepted, and that he personally accepts it.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also stated that if same-sex marriage is in contradiction with one's chosen traditions, then they should not follow it.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, on gender equality and sexism, the Dalai Lama proclaimed at the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, Tennessee: "I call myself a feminist.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Isn't that what you call someone who fights for women's rights?" He also said that by nature, women are more compassionate based on their biology and capacity for reproduction and maternal care.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He called on women to "lead and create a more compassionate world", citing the good works of nurses and mothers.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015 the Dalai Lama said in a BBC interview that if a female were to succeed him, "that female must be attractive, otherwise it is not much use." When asked if he was joking, he replied, "No.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] True!" The Dalai Lama followed with a joke about his success being due to his own appearance.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office later released a statement of apology citing the interaction as a translation error.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2020 statement in *Time* magazine on the COVID-19 pandemic, the Dalai Lama said that the pandemic must be combated with compassion, empirical science, prayer, and the courage of healthcare workers.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised "emotional disarmament" (seeing things with a clear and realistic perspective, without fear or rage) and wrote: "The outbreak of this terrible coronavirus has shown that what happens to one person can soon affect every other being.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In September 2018, speaking at a conference in Malmö, Sweden, the Dalai Lama said "I think Europe belongs to the Europeans", but also that Europe was "morally responsible" for helping "a refugee really facing danger against their life".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He stated that Europe has a responsibility to refugees to "receive them, help them, educate them", but that they should aim to return to their places of origin and that "they ultimately should rebuild their own country".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Speaking to German reporters in 2016, the Dalai Lama said there are "too many" refugees in Europe, adding that "Europe, for example Germany, cannot become an Arab country." He also said that "Germany is Germany".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dorje Shugden is an entity in Tibetan Buddhism that, since the 1930s, has become a point of contention over whether to include or exclude certain non-Gelug teachings.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1975 publication of the *Yellow Book* containing stories about Dorje Shugden acting wrathfully against Gelugpas who also practised Nyingma, the 14th Dalai Lama, himself a Gelugpa and advocate of an inclusive approach, publicly renounced the practice of Dorje Shugden.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Several groups broke away as a result, notably the New Kadampa Tradition (NKT).
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to Tibetologists, the Dalai Lama's disapproval has reduced the prevalence of Shugden sects among Tibetans in China and India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Shugden devotees have since complained about being ostracised when trying to get jobs or receive services.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's supporters expressed that any discrimination is neither systematic nor encouraged by him.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some Shugden movements such as the NKT have organised demonstrations as a form of protest.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some journalists have suggested that the Chinese government has taken advantage of the controversy.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office said that there was no ban or discrimination against Shugden worshippers.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 1998, the Dalai Lama's administration acknowledged that it received $1.7 million a year in the 1960s from the US government through a Central Intelligence Agency program.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked by CIA officer John Kenneth Knaus in 1995 to comment on the CIA Tibetan program, the Dalai Lama replied that though it helped the morale of those resisting the Chinese, "thousands of lives were lost in the resistance" and further, that "the U.S.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Government had involved itself in his country's affairs not to help Tibet but only as a Cold War tactic to challenge the Chinese." As part of the program the Dalai Lama received 180,000 dollars a year from 1959 till 1974 for his own personal use.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His administration's reception of CIA funding has become one of the grounds for some state-run Chinese newspapers to discredit him along with the Tibetan independence movement.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his autobiography *Freedom in Exile*, the Dalai Lama criticised the CIA again for supporting the Tibetan independence movement "not because they (the CIA) cared about Tibetan independence, but as part of their worldwide efforts to destabilize all communist governments".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama places highly in global surveys of the world's most admired men, ranking with Pope Francis as among the world's religious leaders cited as the most admired.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's appeal is variously ascribed to his charismatic personality, international fascination with Buddhism, his universalist values, and international sympathy for the Tibetans.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In the 1990s, many films were released by the American film industry about Tibet, including biopics of the Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This is attributed to both the Dalai Lama's 1989 Nobel Peace Prize as well as to the euphoria following the Fall of Communism.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The most notable films, *Kundun* and *Seven Years in Tibet* (both released in 1997), portrayed "an idyllic pre-1950 Tibet, with a smiling, soft-spoken Dalai Lama at the helm—a Dalai Lama sworn to non-violence": portrayals the Chinese government decried as ahistorical.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has his own pages on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has tried to mobilise international support for Tibetan activities.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has been successful in gaining Western support for himself and the cause of greater Tibetan autonomy, including vocal support from numerous Hollywood celebrities, most notably the actors Richard Gere and Steven Seagal, as well as lawmakers from several major countries.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Photos of the Dalai Lama were banned after March 1959 Lhasa protests until after the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1996 the Chinese Communist Party once again reinstated the total prohibition of any photo of the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Tibet Information Network, "authorities in Tibet have begun banning photographs of the exiled Dalai Lama in monasteries and public places, according to reports from a monitoring group and a Tibetan newspaper.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Plainclothes police went to hotels and restaurants in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, on 22 and 23 April and ordered Tibetans to remove pictures of the Dalai Lama ..." The ban continues in many locations throughout Tibet today.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In popular media, the Dalai Lama appeared on the HBO late-night talk show *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver* on 5 March 2017, where he discussed issues including Tibetan sovereignty, Tibetan self-immolations, and his succession plans.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A biographical graphic novel, *Man of Peace*, also envisaging the Dalai Lama's return to Tibet, was published by Tibet House US.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] *The Extraordinary Life of His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama: An Illuminated Journey,* illustrations and text by artist Rima Fujita, narrated by the Dalai Lama, was published by Simon and Schuster in 2021.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has received numerous awards and honours worldwide over his spiritual and political career.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] For a more complete list see Awards and honours presented to the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, the Norwegian Nobel Committee awarded him the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Committee officially gave the prize to the Dalai Lama for "the struggle of the liberation of Tibet and the efforts for a peaceful resolution" and "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, he became one of only six people ever to be granted Honorary Citizenship of Canada.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2007 he was named Presidential Distinguished Professor at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, the first time he accepted a university appointment.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He is the chief Patron of the Maha Bodhi Society of India, conferred upon him at the 2008 Annual General Meeting of the Maha Bodhi Society of India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At the 68th Annual Grammy Awards, he won the Grammy Award for Best Audio Book, Narration & Storytelling Recording.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a February 2023 video, the Dalai Lama was seen kissing a boy on the lips and asking the child to suck his tongue.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The incident took place at his temple in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, India.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Nearly 100 students were in attendance, as well as the boy's mother, a trustee of the event's organiser.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Her son had requested a hug from the Dalai Lama, who then asked for and received a kiss from the child, pulling him closer to touch lips.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After a pause, the Dalai Lama said "suck my tongue" and, with his tongue out, leaned toward the boy, who appeared nervous and withdrew after sticking out his own tongue.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview clip released by Voice of Tibet, the boy later said it had been a "good experience" meeting the Dalai Lama, from whom he received a lot of "positive energy".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The interaction was originally recorded by Voice of America, which posted the footage after editing out the "suck my tongue" part.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The removed portion of the clip resurfaced in April 2023, and the Dalai Lama's conduct received negative media coverage.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some victim groups and media commentators raised concerns of "child abuse", while the Tibetan Legal Association warned four Indian news outlets to retract parts of their reporting.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The office of His Holiness issued a statement saying that the Dalai Lama often teases "in an innocent and playful way", adding that he "wishes to apologize to the boy and his family ... for the hurt his words may have caused" and "regrets the incident".
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Penpa Tsering, the political leader of the Central Tibetan Administration, called the gesture an "innocent grandfatherly affectionate demeanour" followed by a "jovial prank" with a tongue.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He and other Tibetans accused "pro-Chinese sources" of being behind the video but have not provided any evidence.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some academics, Tibetan leaders and cultural groups described the situation as a cultural misunderstanding.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] They mentioned that sticking out one's tongue is a form of traditional Tibetan greeting to show respect or agreement, stemming from a tradition of performing the gesture to demonstrate that one is not reincarnated from the malevolent king Langdarma, who was said to have a black tongue.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The practice is not known to involve "sucking", however.
[src:european-union/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The controversy also drew attention to past incidents where the Dalai Lama caressed the arm of a disabled girl sitting next to him and touched Lady Gaga's knee through her torn trousers before the star laughed.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] It laid down the realization of Dunant's idea for an independent organization to care and rescue for wounded soldiers.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] Dunant write a book recording his experiences, *Un Souvenir de Solferino* ("A Memory of Solferino", 1862), which he uses as a reminder for his humanitarian advocacy and inspiration for his cause.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] As a prominent economist and politician, Frédéric Passy was involved in many pacifist causes.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] He founded the first French Peace Society, which held a congress in Paris during the 1878 World Exhibition and also was one of the founding fathers of the Inter-Parliamentary Union, an organization for cooperation between the elected representatives of different countries.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] As an independent leftist republic in the French Chamber of Deputies, he opposed France's colonial policy since it went against the principles of free trade and maintained that free trade between independent nations promoted peace.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] Passy continued to campaigning for peace despite his advanced age.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] Despite his economic works gaining little traction, his efforts in the peace movement resulted in him being recognized as the "dean of European peace activists".
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] Henri Dunant was nominated with 20 separate nominations from politicians, academics and heads of peace societies.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] Frédéric Passy, on the other hand, earned 42, making it the highest number of nominations for the year.
[src:european-union/1901-nobel-peace-prize] The Austrian author Bertha von Suttner (awarded in 1905) and American politician Belva Ann Lockwood were the first two women nominated for the peace prize.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Poland on 19 January 1947, the first since World War II.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The largest opposition party, the Polish People's Party, was officially credited with 28 seats; however, the elections were characterized by violence; anti-Communist opposition candidates and activists were persecuted by the Volunteer Reserve Militia (ORMO).
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The elections were heavily manipulated, and the opposition claimed that it would have won in a landslide had the election been conducted in a fair manner.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The election gave the Soviets, as well as the Communist-dominated Polish satellite government, enough legitimacy to claim that Poland was "free and democratic", thus allowing Poland to sign the charter of the United Nations.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] By 1946, Poland was mostly under the control of the Soviet Union and its proxies, the PPR.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] In 1946, the Communists already tested their strength by falsifying the "3xYES Referendum", and banning the vast majority of right-wing parties (under the pretext of their pro-Nazi stance).
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] By 1947, the only remaining legal opposition was the Polish People's Party (PSL) of Stanisław Mikołajczyk.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The Yalta agreement called for "free and unfettered" elections in Poland.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] However, the Kremlin and the PPR had no intention of permitting an honest election.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Soviet leader Joseph Stalin was well aware that if Poland held a free election, it would result in an anti-Soviet government.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Conditioned in part by the Hungarian Communists' weak showing in 1945, the PPR proposed to present voters with a single list from all of the legal parties in the country.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The PSL rejected this proposal almost out of hand.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Eventually, only the PPS, SD and SL joined the Democratic Bloc.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Every electoral district had Democratic Bloc's candidates on List 3.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The January 1947 elections held under the supervision of the PPR fell well short of being "free and unfettered".
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The PPR, under the leadership of general secretary Władysław Gomułka, embarked on a ruthless campaign to snuff out the PSL and all other potential opposition.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Over 80,000 members of the Polish People's Party were arrested under various false charges in the month preceding the election, and around 100 of them were murdered by the Polish Secret Police (Urząd Bezpieczeństwa, UB).
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] 98 opposition parliamentary candidates were also crossed from the registration lists under these accusations.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] In some regions the government disqualified the entire People's Party list under various technical and legal pretenses, most commonly in regions known to be People's Party strongholds.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The electoral fraud was organized and closely monitored by UB specialists, who worked closely with their Soviet counterparts like Aron Palkin and Semyon Davydov, both high-ranking officers from the Soviet MGB.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Bolesław Bierut, head of the provisional Polish parliament (State National Council) and acting president, asked for Soviet assistance in the election.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Over 40% of the members of the electoral commissions who were supposed to monitor the voting were recruited by the UB.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Opposition candidates and activists were persecuted until election day; only the PPR and its allies were allowed to campaign unhindered.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The publicized results were falsified, with the official results known to selected government officials long before the actual elections took place and any votes were counted.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The real results were not known to anyone.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] In areas where the government had sufficient control, some of the ballot boxes were simply destroyed without being counted, or exchanged with boxes filled with prepared votes.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Where possible, government officials simply filled in the numbers in the relevant documents as per instructions from Soviet and PPR officials without bothering to count the real votes.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] A *Time* article covering the elections noted in its lead paragraph: "In a spirit of partisan exuberance tempered with terror, Poland approached its first nationwide popular election, ten days hence.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] By last week most of the combined opposition (Socialist and Polish Peasant Party) candidates had been jailed, and their supporters more or less completely cowed by the secret police, by striking their names from voting lists and by arrest.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The Communist-dominated Government ventured to predict an 'overwhelming' victory." Historian Piotr Wrobel wrote that this election saw "the highest level of repression and terror" that was ever seen during the four decades of Communist rule in Poland.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] In his post-election report to Stalin, Pałkin estimated that the real results (i.e. votes cast) gave the Democratic Bloc about 50% of the vote.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The opposition contended that it had the support of 63 percent of the voting population, and would have received about 80% of the votes, had the elections been free and fair.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The only official electoral document known to exist showed the PSL taking 54 percent of the vote in Kielce Voivodeship to the Democratic Bloc's 44 percent.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Many members of opposition parties, including Mikołajczyk who would have likely become the Prime Minister of Poland had the election been honest, saw no hope in further struggle; fearing for their lives, they left the country.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Western governments issued only token protests, if any, which led many anti-Communist Poles to speak of postwar "Western betrayal".
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] In the same year, the new Communist-dominated legislative Sejm adopted the Small Constitution of 1947, and Bierut, who was also a Soviet citizen, was elected president by the parliament.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Gomułka wanted to adapt the Soviet blueprint to Polish circumstances, and believed it was possible to be both a Communist and a Polish patriot at the same time.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] He was also wary of the Cominform and opposed forced collectivization of agriculture.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] His line was branded as "rightist-nationalist deviation", and he was pushed out as party leader in 1948 in favour of Bierut.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The PSL lingered on for a year and a half under increasing harassment.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] In 1949, the rump of the PSL merged with the pro-Communist People's Party to form the United People's Party.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] Along with the other legal minor party in Poland, the Democratic Party, it was part of the Communist-led coalition; however, this grouping increasingly took on a character similar to other "coalitions" in the Communist world.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] The ZSL and SD were reduced to being mostly subservient satellites of the Communists, and were required to accept the Communists' "leading role" as a condition of their continued existence.
[src:european-union/1947-polish-legislative-election] As a result, this would be the last election in which true opposition parties would be even nominally allowed to take part until the partly free election of 1989.
[src:european-union/eu] The .eu ccTLD was approved by ICANN on 22 March 2005 and put in the Internet root zone on 2 May 2005.
[src:european-union/eu] Even though the EU is not a country (it is a sui generis intergovernmental and supranational organisation), it has an exceptional reservation in ISO 3166.
[src:european-union/eu] The Commission and ICANN had extended negotiations lasting more than five years to secure its acceptance.
[src:european-union/eu] The sunrise period was broken into two phases.
[src:european-union/eu] The first phase, which began on 7 December 2005 was to facilitate applications by registrants with prior rights based on trademarks and geographic names.
[src:european-union/eu] The second phase began on 7 February 2006 and covered company, trade and personal names.
[src:european-union/eu] In the case of all Sunrise applications, the application needed to be accompanied by documents proving the claim to ownership of a certain right.
[src:european-union/eu] The decision was then made by PricewaterhouseCoopers Belgium, which had been chosen as the validation agent by EURid.
[src:european-union/eu] On 7 February 2006, the registry was opened for company, trade and personal names.
[src:european-union/eu] In the first 15 minutes, there were 27,949 total applications, and after one hour, 71,235.
[src:european-union/eu] On 7 April 2006 at 11 am CET registration became possible for non-trademark holders.
[src:european-union/eu] Most people requesting domains had asked their registrars to put their requested domains in a queue, ensuring the best chance to register a domain.
[src:european-union/eu] This way more than 700,000 domains were registered during the first 4 hours of operation.
[src:european-union/eu] Some large registrars like GoDaddy and small registrars like Dotster suffered from long queues and unresponsiveness, allowing people to 'beat the queue' by registering through a registrar that had already processed its queue.
[src:european-union/eu] By August 2006, 2 Million .eu domains had been registered.
[src:european-union/eu] It was then fourth-largest ccTLD in Europe, after .de, .uk and .nl, and is one of the largest internationally.
[src:european-union/eu] The number of .eu domain registrations during the year after the landrush 7 April 2006 to 6 April 2007 seems to have peaked at approximately 2.6 million .eu domains.
[src:european-union/eu] The market adjustment that follows a landrush in any domain name extension ensures that the number of registered domains will fall as many speculative domain registrations that failed to be resold will not be renewed.
[src:european-union/eu] This is sometimes referred to as the *Junk Dump*.
[src:european-union/eu] On the morning of 7 April 2007, the number of active .eu domains stood at 2,590,160 with approximately 15,000 domains having been deleted since 5 April 2007.
[src:european-union/eu] Approximately 1.5 million .eu domains were up for renewal in April 2007.
[src:european-union/eu] The EURid registry software is based on the DNS.be software and domains are physically renewed at the end of the month of their anniversary of registration.
[src:european-union/eu] This process differs from more sophisticated registries like that of .com TLD and other ccTLDs that operate on a daily basis.
[src:european-union/eu] As with any post-landrush phase, an extension shrinks as the *Junk Dump* takes effect.
[src:european-union/eu] Over one year after the launch of .eu (5 July 2007), the number of .de domains registered was 11,079,557 according to the German .de registry's statistics page, while number of German owned .eu domains according to EURid's statistics page was 796,561.
[src:european-union/eu] The number of .uk domains registered was 6,038,732 according to .uk registry Nominet's statistics page.
[src:european-union/eu] The number of apparently UK owned .eu domains was 344,584.
[src:european-union/eu] The extent of the shrinkage of .eu ccTLD is difficult to estimate because EURid does not publish detailed statistics on the number of new domains registered each day.
[src:european-union/eu] Instead it provides only a single figure for the number of active domains.
[src:european-union/eu] The number of new registrations are combined with numbers of domains registered.
[src:european-union/eu] Approximately 250,000 .eu domains were either deleted or moved into quarantine by 30 April 2007.
[src:european-union/eu] In the intervening years the renewal rate has stabilised to approximately 80%, which is above the industry average.
[src:european-union/eu] As of November 2019, according to the Tranco rank, the top 100 thousand most popular domains in the world included over 200 .eu domains.
[src:european-union/eu] The commission announced on 27 April 2018 that it would like to open registration to all EU and EEA citizens, including those living outside the EU.
[src:european-union/eu] The Parliament, the council, and the Commission reached an agreement on this in December 2018, and the corresponding regulation passed the Parliament on 31 January 2019.
[src:european-union/eu] The 317,000 British .eu domain names were subject to Brexit negotiations because the .eu domain is reserved for European Union use.
[src:european-union/eu] The .eu Brexit would have occurred on 30 March 2020, in case of no deal, but had since been postponed to January 2021.
[src:european-union/eu] The UK-EU free trade deal does not cover .eu domains.
[src:european-union/eu] The United Kingdom Government released guidance for British citizens regarding .eu domains in October 2020, and .eu holders with a British address attached have been contacted twice by the domain registry regarding their domains – once in October 2020, once in December 2020.
[src:european-union/eu] British citizens had their .eu domains suspended on 1 January 2021 for six months, and then withdrawn on 1 July 2021 after a grace period to allow EU/EEA citizens to update the registration information to show their non-UK address.
[src:european-union/eu] From 1 January 2022, they were revoked and made available for registration by other entities.
[src:european-union/eu] This is the first case of its kind where an institution managing an internet top-level domain has withdrawn domains *en masse* for an entire country.
[src:european-union/eu] The second-level domain .europa.eu has been reserved for EU institution sites, with institutions and agencies making the switch from .eu.int to .europa.eu domains on the Europe day of 9 May 2006.
[src:european-union/eu] EURid has a rule that the second-level domain name must be in the same script as the top-level domain, so Cyrillic second-level domains must go under .ею instead of .eu, and all domain names under .ею must be spelt using Cyrillic.
[src:european-union/eu] Older Cyrillic domains under .eu were cloned into .ею at its launch.
[src:european-union/eu] As of March 2024, there are 1,486 registered domains under .ею.
[src:european-union/eu] An application for a top-level domain using Greek letters, **.ευ** was submitted in 2016.
[src:european-union/eu] The application was originally turned down because it was too visually similar to .eu.
[src:european-union/eu] The Greek name of the EU is Ευρωπαϊκή Ένωση (ΕΕ), but .εε would be too visually similar to .ee, the top-level domain of Estonia.
[src:european-union/eu] In 2019 steps were taken towards approving .ευ as a domain.
[src:european-union/eu] As of March 2024, there are 2,595 registered domains under .ευ.
[src:european-union/eu] Domain name speculation, domain name warehousing and cybersquatting are always features of the launch of any new TLD; however, this was more widespread in the case of the .eu launch.
[src:european-union/eu] Bob Parsons, CEO and co-founder of GoDaddy, criticized the landrush process designed by EURid.
[src:european-union/eu] Particularly, he condemned the use of shell companies by some registrars.
[src:european-union/eu] These "phantom" registrars effectively had hundreds of opportunities of registering a domain whereas a genuine registrar effectively only had one opportunity to register the same domain.
[src:european-union/eu] Thus some registrants were crowded out of the .eu landrush process and many generic .eu domain names are now owned by the companies using these "phantom" registrars.
[src:european-union/eu] Patrik Lindén, spokesman for EURid at the time, denied the allegations by Parsons, stating that "[EURid] verified that each registrar was an individual legal entity.
[src:european-union/eu] Each had to sign an agreement with us, and prepay €10,000." Parsons did not dispute that each registrar was a separate legal entity, but noted that creating such entities was trivial: "Mr.
[src:european-union/eu] Linden seemed proud that the EURid registry verified that each applicant was a legal entity before it was accredited.
[src:european-union/eu] Take a moment and think about what that means.
[src:european-union/eu] You can form a "legal entity" for $50 – an LLC – and you are good to go.
[src:european-union/eu] While speculative activity occurred with the launch of other domains, it was the scale of the activity that called into question the competence of EURid in protecting the integrity of eu ccTLD.
[src:european-union/eu] The EURid organisation investigated some allegations of abuse, and in July 2006 announced the suspension of over 74,000 domain names and that they were suing 400 registrars for breach of contract.
[src:european-union/eu] The status of the domains was changed from *active* to *on-hold*.
[src:european-union/eu] This meant that the domains could not be moved or have their ownership changed.
[src:european-union/eu] The registrars also lost their access to the EURid registration database meaning that they could no longer register .eu domain names.
[src:european-union/eu] The legal action relates to the practice of domain name warehousing, whereby large numbers of domain names are registered, often by registrars, with the intention of subsequently selling them on to third parties.
[src:european-union/eu] EURid rules state that applications for domains can only be made after a legitimate application has been made to a registrar.
[src:european-union/eu] The 74,000 applications were made in the name of only three Cyprus registered companies – Ovidio Ltd., Fausto Ltd. and Gabino Ltd.
[src:european-union/eu] The affected registrars, joined in the action by the affected registrants, obtained a provisional order from the Court of First Instance in Brussels, Belgium on 27 September 2006.
[src:european-union/eu] The court ordered EURid to release the blocked domain names or else pay a fine of €25,000 per hour for each affected domain name.
[src:european-union/eu] EURid complied with the court order and changed the status of the domains from *on-hold* to *active* and restored EURid registration database access to the affected registrars.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The **European Union** (**EU**) is a political and economic union of 27 member states that are located primarily in Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The EU is often described as a *sui generis* political entity combining characteristics of both a federation and a confederation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Its cornerstone, the Customs Union, paved the way to establishing an internal single market based on standardised legal framework and legislation that applies in all member states in those matters, and only those matters, where the states have agreed to act as one.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] EU policies aim to ensure the free movement of people, goods, services and capital within the internal market; enact legislation in justice and home affairs; and maintain common policies on trade, agriculture, fisheries, and regional development.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Passport controls have been abolished for travel within the Schengen Area.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The eurozone is a group composed of the 21 EU member states that have fully implemented the EU's economic and monetary union and use the euro currency.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Through the Common Foreign and Security Policy, the union has developed a role in external relations and defence.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] It maintains permanent diplomatic missions throughout the world and represents itself at the United Nations, the World Trade Organization, the G7 and the G20.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2012, the EU was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The EU was established, along with its citizenship, when the Maastricht Treaty came into force in 1993, and was incorporated as an international legal juridical person upon entry into force of the Treaty of Lisbon in 2009.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] These increasingly amalgamated bodies grew, with their legal successor the EU, both in size through the accessions of a further 22 states from 1973 to 2013, and in power through acquisitions of policy areas.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2020, the United Kingdom became the only member state to leave the EU; ten countries are aspiring or negotiating to join it.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Internationalism and visions of European unity had existed since well before the 19th century, but gained particularly as a reaction to World War I and its aftermath.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In this light the first advances for the idea of European integration were made.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] With large-scale war being waged in Europe once again in the 1930s and becoming World War II, the question of what to fight against and what for had to be agreed on.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] A first agreement was the Declaration of St James's Palace of 1941, when Europe's resistance gathered in London.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] This was expanded on by the 1941 Atlantic Charter, establishing the Allies and their common goals, inciting a new wave of global international institutions like the United Nations (founded 1945) or the Bretton Woods System (1944).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1943 at the Moscow Conference and Tehran Conference, plans to establish joint institutions for a post-war world and Europe increasingly became a part of the agenda.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] This led to a decision at the Yalta Conference in 1944 to form a European Advisory Commission, later replaced by the Council of Foreign Ministers and the Allied Control Council, following the German surrender and the Potsdam Agreement in 1945.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] By the end of the war, European integration became seen as an antidote to the extreme nationalism that had caused the war.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] One month later, the French Union was installed by the new Fourth French Republic to direct the decolonisation of its colonies so that they would become parts of a European community.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] By 1947, a growing rift between the western Allied Powers and the Soviet Union became evident as a result of the rigged 1947 Polish legislative election, which constituted an open breach of the Yalta Agreement.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] March of that year saw two important developments.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] First was the signing of the Treaty of Dunkirk between France and the United Kingdom.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The treaty assured mutual assistance in the event of future military aggression against either nation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Though it officially named Germany as a threat, in reality the actual concern was for the Soviet Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] A few days later came the announcement of the Truman Doctrine which pledged American support for democracies to counter the Soviets.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Immediately following the February 1948 coup d'état by the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia, the London Six-Power Conference was held, resulting in the Soviet boycott of the Allied Control Council and its incapacitation, an event marking the beginning of the Cold War.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The year 1948 marked the beginning of the institutionalised modern European integration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In March 1948 the Treaty of Brussels was signed, establishing the Western Union (WU), followed by the International Authority for the Ruhr.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Furthermore, the Organisation for European Economic Co-operation (OEEC), the predecessor of the OECD, was also founded in 1948 to manage the Marshall Plan, which led to the Soviets creating Comecon in response.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The ensuing Hague Congress of May 1948 was a pivotal moment in European integration, as it led to the creation of the European Movement International, the College of Europe, and most importantly to the foundation of the Council of Europe on 5 May 1949 (which is now Europe Day).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The Council of Europe was one of the first institutions to bring the sovereign states of (then only Western) Europe together, raising great hopes and fevered debates in the following two years for further European integration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] It has since been a broad forum to further cooperation and shared issues, achieving for example the European Convention on Human Rights in 1950.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Essential for the actual birth of the institutions of the EU was the Schuman Declaration on 9 May 1950 (the day after the fifth Victory in Europe Day) and the decision by six nations (France, Belgium, Netherlands, Luxembourg, West Germany, and Italy) to follow Schuman and draft the Treaty of Paris.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] This treaty was created in 1952 the European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC), which was built on the International Authority for the Ruhr, installed by the Western Allies in 1949 to regulate the coal and steel industries of the Ruhr area in West Germany.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Backed by the Marshall Plan with large funds coming from the United States since 1948, the ECSC became a milestone organisation, enabling European economic development and integration and being the origin of the main institutions of the EU such as the European Commission and Parliament.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The founding fathers of the European Union understood that coal and steel were the two industries essential for waging war, and believed that by tying their national industries together, a future war between their nations became much less likely.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1954 the Modified Brussels Treaty transformed the Western Union into the Western European Union (WEU).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] West Germany eventually joined both the WEU and NATO in 1955, prompting the Soviet Union to form the Warsaw Pact in 1955 as an institutional framework for its military domination in the countries of Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Assessing the progress of European integration the Messina Conference was held in 1955, ordering the Spaak Report, which in 1956 recommended the next significant steps of European integration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1957, Belgium, France, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and West Germany signed the Treaty of Rome, which created the European Economic Community (EEC) and established a customs union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] They also signed another pact creating the European Atomic Energy Community (Euratom) for cooperation in developing nuclear power.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Although the EEC and Euratom were created separately from the ECSC, they shared the same courts and the Common Assembly.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The EEC was headed by Walter Hallstein (Hallstein Commission) and Euratom was headed by Louis Armand (Armand Commission) and then Étienne Hirsch (Hirsch Commission).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The OEEC was in turn reformed in 1961 into the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and its membership was extended to states outside of Europe, the United States and Canada.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] During the 1960s, tensions began to show, with France seeking to limit supranational power.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Nevertheless, in 1965 an agreement was reached, and on 1 July 1967 the Merger Treaty created a single set of institutions for the three communities, which were collectively referred to as the *European Communities*.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Jean Rey presided over the first merged commission (Rey Commission).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1973, the communities were enlarged to include Denmark (including Greenland), Ireland, and the United Kingdom.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Norway had negotiated to join at the same time, but Norwegian voters rejected membership in a referendum.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The *Ostpolitik* and the ensuing détente led to establishment of a first truly pan-European body, the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE), predecessor of the modern Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1979, the first direct elections to the European Parliament were held.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1985, Greenland left the Communities, following a dispute over fishing rights.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] During the same year, the Schengen Agreement paved the way for the creation of open borders without passport controls between most member states and some non-member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1986, the Single European Act was signed.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1990, after the fall of the Eastern Bloc, the former East Germany became part of the communities as part of a reunified Germany.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The European Union was formally established when the Maastricht Treaty—whose main architects were Horst Köhler, Helmut Kohl and François Mitterrand—came into force on 1 November 1993.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The treaty also gave the name *European Community* to the EEC, even if it was referred to as such before the treaty.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] With further enlargement planned to include the former communist states of Central and Eastern Europe, as well as Cyprus and Malta, the Copenhagen criteria for candidate members to join the EU were agreed upon in June 1993.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The expansion of the EU introduced a new level of complexity and discord.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 1995, Austria, Finland, and Sweden joined the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2002, euro banknotes and coins replaced national currencies in 12 of the member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Since then, the eurozone has increased to encompass 21 countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The euro currency became the second-largest reserve currency in the world.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2004, the EU saw its biggest enlargement to date when Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia joined the union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2007, Bulgaria and Romania became EU members.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Later that year, Slovenia adopted the euro, followed by Cyprus and Malta in 2008, Slovakia in 2009, Estonia in 2011, Latvia in 2014, Lithuania in 2015, and Croatia in 2023.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] On 1 December 2009, the Lisbon Treaty entered into force and reformed many aspects of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2012, the EU received the Nobel Peace Prize for having "contributed to the advancement of peace and reconciliation, democracy, and human rights in Europe".
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In 2013, Croatia became the 28th EU member.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] From the beginning of the 2010s, the cohesion of the European Union has been tested by several issues, including the euro area crisis, 2015 European migrant crisis, and Brexit.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] A referendum in the UK on its membership of the European Union was held in 2016, with 51.9 per cent of participants voting to leave.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The early 2020s saw Denmark abolishing one of its three opt-outs and Croatia adopting the euro.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] After the economic crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, the EU leaders agreed for the first time to create common debt to finance the European Recovery Program called Next Generation EU (NGEU).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] On 24 February 2022, after massing on the borders of Ukraine, the Russian Armed Forces undertook an attempt for a full-scale invasion of Ukraine.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The European Union imposed heavy sanctions on Russia and agreed on a pooled military aid package to Ukraine for lethal weapons funded via the European Peace Facility off-budget instrument.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] NGEU is a European Commission economic recovery package to support the EU member states to recover from the COVID-19 pandemic, in particular those that have been particularly hard hit.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] It is sometimes styled NextGenerationEU and Next Gen EU, and also called the European Union Recovery Instrument.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Agreed in principle by the European Council on 21 July 2020 and adopted on 14 December 2020, the instrument is worth €750 billion.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] NGEU will operate from 2021 to 2026, and will be tied to the regular 2021–2027 budget of the EU's Multiannual Financial Framework (MFF).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The comprehensive NGEU and MFF packages are projected to reach €1824.3 billion.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Preparing the EU for a new great enlargement is one of its political priorities, with the goal of achieving 35 member states by 2030.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Institutional and budgetary reforms are being discussed in order for the EU to be ready for the new members.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] In December 2025, it was leaked that the United States government would attempt to persuade "Austria, Hungary, Italy, and Poland" to depart the EU in a Brexit-type manner.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The following timeline outlines the legal inception of the European Union (EU)—the principal framework for this unification.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The EU inherited many of its present organisations, institutions, and responsibilities from the European Communities (EC), which were founded in the 1950s in the spirit of the Schuman Declaration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Plans to establish a European Political Community (EPC) were shelved following the French failure to ratify the Treaty establishing the European Defence Community (EDC).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The EPC would have combined the ECSC and the EDC.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The European Communities obtained common institutions and a shared legal personality (i.e. ability to e.g. sign treaties in their own right).
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The treaties of Maastricht and Rome form the EU's legal basis, and are also referred to as the Treaty on European Union (TEU) and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU), respectively.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Between the EU's founding in 1993 and consolidation in 2009, the union consisted of three pillars, the first of which were the European Communities.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The other two pillars consisted of additional areas of cooperation that had been added to the EU's remit.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] The consolidation meant that the EU inherited the European Communities' legal personality and that the pillar system was abolished, resulting in the EU framework as such covering all policy areas.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] Executive/legislative power in each area was instead determined by a distribution of competencies between EU institutions and member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p01] This distribution, as well as treaty provisions for policy areas in which unanimity is required and qualified majority voting is possible, reflects the depth of EU integration as well as the EU's partly supranational and partly intergovernmental nature.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Laws made by the EU institutions are passed in a variety of forms.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Generally speaking, they can be classified into two groups: those which come into force without the necessity for national implementation measures (regulations) and those which specifically require national implementation measures (directives).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EU policy is in general promulgated by EU directives, which are then implemented in the domestic legislation of its member states, and EU regulations, which are immediately enforceable in all member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Lobbying at the EU level by special interest groups is regulated to try to balance the aspirations of private initiatives with public interest decision-making process.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Through successive enlargements, the EU and its predecessors have grown from the six founding states of the EEC to 27 members.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Countries accede to the union by becoming a party to the founding treaties, thereby subjecting themselves to the privileges and obligations of EU membership.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] This entails a partial delegation of sovereignty to the institutions in return for representation within those institutions, a practice often referred to as "pooling of sovereignty".
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In some policies, there are several member states that ally with strategic partners within the union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Examples of such alliances include the Baltic Assembly, the Benelux Union, the Bucharest Nine, the Craiova Group, the EU Med Group, the Lublin Triangle, the New Hanseatic League, the Three Seas Initiative, the Visegrád Group, and the Weimar Triangle.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] To become a member, a country must meet the Copenhagen criteria, defined at the 1993 meeting of the European Council in Copenhagen.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] These require a stable democracy that respects human rights and the rule of law; a functioning market economy; and the acceptance of the obligations of membership, including EU law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Evaluation of a country's fulfilment of the criteria is the responsibility of the European Council.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The relationships of the European microstates Andorra, Monaco, San Marino, and Vatican City include the use of the euro and other areas of co-operation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Subdivisions of member-states are based on the Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics (NUTS), a geocode standard for statistical purposes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The standard, adopted in 2003, is developed and regulated by the European Union, and thus only covers the member states of the EU in detail.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics is instrumental in the European Union's Structural Funds and Cohesion Fund delivery mechanisms and for locating the area where goods and services subject to European public procurement legislation are to be delivered.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] There are nine countries that are recognised as candidates for membership: Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, Moldova, Montenegro, North Macedonia, Serbia, Turkey, and Ukraine.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Norway, Switzerland and Iceland have submitted membership applications in the past, but subsequently froze or withdrew them.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Iceland is holding a referendum on resuming membership negotiations in August 2026.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Additionally Kosovo is officially recognised as a potential candidate, and has submitted a membership application.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty provides the basis for a member to leave the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Two territories have left the union: Greenland (an autonomous province of Denmark) withdrew in 1985; the United Kingdom formally invoked Article 50 of the Consolidated Treaty on European Union in 2017, and became the only sovereign state to leave when it withdrew from the EU in 2020.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Member states retain in principle all powers except those that they have agreed collectively to delegate to the union as a whole, though the exact delimitation has on occasions become a subject of scholarly or legal disputes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In certain fields, members have awarded exclusive competence and exclusive mandate to the union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] These are areas in which member states have entirely renounced their own capacity to enact legislation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In other areas, the EU and its member states share the competence to legislate.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] While both can legislate, the member states can only legislate to the extent to which the EU has not.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In other policy areas, the EU can only co-ordinate, support and supplement member state action but cannot enact legislation with the aim of harmonising national laws.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] That a particular policy area falls into a certain category of competence is not necessarily indicative of what legislative procedure is used for enacting legislation within that policy area.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Different legislative procedures are used within the same category of competence, and even with the same policy area.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union has seven principal decision-making bodies, its institutions: the European Parliament, the European Council, the Council of the European Union, the European Commission, the Court of Justice of the European Union, the European Central Bank and the European Court of Auditors.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The monetary policy of the eurozone is determined by the European Central Bank.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The interpretation and the application of EU law and the treaties are ensured by the Court of Justice of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU budget is scrutinised by the European Court of Auditors.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] There are also a number of ancillary bodies which advise the EU or operate in a specific area.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The union's executive branch is organised as a directorial system, where the executive power is jointly exercised by several people.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The executive branch consists of the European Council and European Commission.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Council sets the broad political direction of the union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It convenes at least four times a year and comprises the president of the European Council (presently António Costa), the president of the European Commission and one representative per member state (either its head of state or head of government).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The high representative of the union for foreign affairs and security policy (presently Kaja Kallas) also takes part in its meetings.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Described by some as the union's "supreme political leadership", it is actively involved in the negotiation of treaty changes and defines the EU's policy agenda and strategies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Its leadership role involves solving disputes between member states and the institutions, and to resolving any political crises or disagreements over controversial issues and policies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It acts as a "collective head of state" and ratifies important documents (for example, international agreements and treaties).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Tasks for the president of the European Council are ensuring the external representation of the EU, driving consensus and resolving divergences among member states, both during meetings of the European Council and over the periods between them.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Council should not be mistaken for the Council of Europe, an international organisation independent of the EU and based in Strasbourg.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Commission acts both as the EU's executive arm, responsible for the day-to-day running of the EU, and also the legislative initiator, with the sole power to propose laws for debate.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The commission is 'guardian of the Treaties' and is responsible for their efficient operation and policing.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It has 27 European commissioners for different areas of policy, one from each member state, though commissioners are bound to represent the interests of the EU as a whole rather than their home state.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The leader of the 27 is the president of the European Commission (presently Ursula von der Leyen for 2019–2024, reelected for the 2024–2029 term), proposed by the European Council, following and taking into account the result of the European elections, and is then elected by the European Parliament.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The President retains, as the leader responsible for the entire cabinet, the final say in accepting or rejecting a candidate submitted for a given portfolio by a member state, and oversees the commission's permanent civil service.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] After the President, the most prominent commissioner is the high representative of the union for foreign affairs and security policy, who is *ex-officio* a vice-president of the European Commission and is also chosen by the European Council.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The other 25 commissioners are subsequently appointed by the Council of the European Union in agreement with the nominated president.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The 27 commissioners as a single body are subject to approval (or otherwise) by a vote of the European Parliament.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] All commissioners are first nominated by the government of the respective member state.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The council, as it is now simply called (also called the Council of the European Union and the "Council of Ministers", its former title), forms one half of the EU's legislature.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It consists of a representative from each member state's government and meets in different compositions depending on the policy area being addressed.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Notwithstanding its different configurations, it is considered to be one single body.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In addition to the legislative functions, members of the council also have executive responsibilities, such as the development of a Common Foreign and Security Policy and the coordination of broad economic policies within the union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Presidency of the council rotates between member states, with each holding it for six months.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Beginning on 1 July 2025, the position is held by Denmark.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Parliament is one of three legislative institutions of the EU, which together with the Council of the European Union is tasked with amending and approving the European Commission's proposals.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] 705 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) are directly elected by EU citizens every five years on the basis of proportional representation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] MEPs are elected on a national basis and they sit according to political groups rather than their nationality.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Each country has a set number of seats and is divided into sub-national constituencies where this does not affect the proportional nature of the voting system.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In the ordinary legislative procedure, the European Commission proposes legislation, which requires the joint approval of the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union to pass.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] This process applies to nearly all areas, including the EU budget.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The parliament is the final body to approve or reject the proposed membership of the commission, and can attempt motions of censure on the commission by appeal to the Court of Justice.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The president of the European Parliament carries out the role of speaker in Parliament and represents it externally.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The president and vice-presidents are elected by MEPs every two and a half years.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The judicial branch of the European Union is formally called the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU) and consists of two courts: the Court of Justice and the General Court.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Court of Justice is the supreme court of the European Union in matters of European Union law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] As a part of the CJEU, it is tasked with interpreting EU law and ensuring its uniform application across all EU member states under Article 263 of the Treaty of the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Court was established in 1952, and is based in Luxembourg.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It is composed of one judge per member state – currently 27 – although it normally hears cases in panels of three, five or fifteen judges.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Court has been led by president Koen Lenaerts since 2015.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The CJEU is the highest court of the European Union in matters of Union law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Its case-law provides that EU law has supremacy over any national law that is inconsistent with EU law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It is not possible to appeal against the decisions of national courts in the CJEU, but rather national courts refer questions of EU law to the CJEU (a preliminary reference).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] However, it is ultimately for the national court to apply the resulting interpretation (the preliminary ruling) to the facts of any given case.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Although, only courts of final appeal are bound to refer a question of EU law when one is addressed.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The treaties give the CJEU the power for consistent application of EU law across the EU as a whole.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The court also acts as an administrative and constitutional court between the other EU institutions and the Member States and can annul or invalidate unlawful acts of EU institutions, bodies, offices and agencies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The General Court is a constituent court of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It hears actions taken against the institutions of the European Union by individuals and member states, although certain matters are reserved for the Court of Justice.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Decisions of the General Court can be appealed to the Court of Justice, but only on a point of law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Prior to the coming into force of the Lisbon Treaty on 1 December 2009, it was known as the Court of First Instance.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Since the amendments to the Statute of the CJEU in October 2024, the Court of Justice shares its jurisdiction over references for a preliminary ruling with the General Court.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Central Bank (ECB) is one of the institutions of the monetary branch of the European Union, the prime component of the Eurosystem and the European System of Central Banks.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It is one of the world's most important central banks.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The ECB Governing Council makes monetary policy for the eurozone and the European Union, administers the foreign exchange reserves of EU member states, engages in foreign exchange operations, and defines the intermediate monetary objectives and key interest rate of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The ECB Executive Board enforces the policies and decisions of the Governing Council, and may direct the national central banks when doing so.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The ECB has the exclusive right to authorise the issuance of euro banknotes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Member states can issue euro coins, but the volume must be approved by the ECB beforehand.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The bank also operates the T2 (RTGS) payments system.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European System of Central Banks (ESCB) consists of the ECB and the national central banks (NCBs) of all 27 member states of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The ESCB is not the monetary authority of the eurozone, because not all EU member states have joined the euro.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The ESCB's objective is price stability throughout the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Secondarily, the ESCB's goal is to improve monetary and financial cooperation between the Eurosystem and member states outside the eurozone.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Court of Auditors (ECA) is the auditory branch of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It was established in 1975 in Luxembourg in order to improve EU financial management.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It has 27 members (1 from each EU member-state) supported by approximately 800 civil servants.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Personnel Selection Office (EPSO) is the EU's civil service recruitment body and operates its selection of candidates via generalist and specialist competitions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Each institution is then able to recruit staff from among the pool of candidates selected by EPSO.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] On average, EPSO receives around 60,000–70,000 applications a year with around 1,500–2,000 candidates recruited by the European Union institutions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Ombudsman is the ombudsman branch of the European Union that holds the institutions, bodies and agencies of the EU to account, and promotes good administration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Ombudsman helps people, businesses and organisations facing problems with the EU administration by investigating complaints, as well as by proactively looking into broader systemic issues.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The current Ombudsman is Teresa Anjinho.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Public Prosecutor's Office (EPPO) is the prosecutory branch of the union with juridical personality, established under the Treaty of Lisbon between 23 of the 27 states of the EU following the method of enhanced cooperation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union’s public ethics system is highly fragmented, with various bespoke public integrity regimes coexisting under EU law, each possessing its own ethics principles and obligations.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EU ethics standards are scattered across multiple legal sources, ranging from the EU Treaties and institutional Rules of Procedure to Codes of Conduct and the EU Staff Regulations.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] While public ethics instruments exist in almost all EU institutions, there is less evidence that ethics constitutes an integrated feature of day-to-day EU policymaking, a concept defined by scholars as "ethical governance".
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Historically, the system's enforcement mechanisms have faced severe structural limitations, notably high fragmentation, limited independence, and weak sanctioning powers.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Furthermore, virtually all EU institutions have traditionally entrusted the respect of these rules to themselves through internal self-assessment mechanisms rather than independent external oversight.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The 2022 Qatargate influence-buying scandal served as a critical juncture that accelerated the push for systemic reform across the institutions, as public perception of the transparency and independence of EU institutions vis-à-vis private interests remained poor.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 2021, the European Parliament had initially proposed the creation of a strong, independent ethics body equipped with its own investigative and enforcement powers.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Instead, the main EU institutions concluded an agreement, formally signed in May 2024, to establish a comparatively constrained Interinstitutional Body for Ethical Standards (IBES).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The core task of this new entity is the development of "common minimum standards" for the conduct of the political members of the participating institutions, strictly excluding the EU civil service staff.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The new body adopts these minimum standards by consensus and is assisted by five independent experts.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Court of Justice of the EU (ECJ) participates only as an observer to preserve its judicial impartiality.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Interinstitutional EU Ethics Body (or Interinstitutional Body for Ethical Standards; IBES) faces specific legal and constitutional constraints.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Functioning through the "contractual" conjunction of each participating institution, the body operates primarily as a formal mechanism for coordination rather than a centralized enforcement agency.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Curiously the body is not based on the Treaty legal basis for IIAs (Inter Institutional Agreements) (Article 295 TFEU), as this article only refers to the three main EU institutions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It cannot take over decision-making powers for individual disciplinary cases..
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Consequently, it does not replace existing ethical authorities but merely aims at complementing them, and its creation explicitly does not encroach upon the investigative competences of the European Anti-Fraud Office (OLAF) or the European Ombudsman.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Ombudsman continues to play a parallel role in assessing ethical breaches and conflicts of interests under the broader concept of "maladministration", which goes beyond strict illegality.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Academic evaluations and civil society groups generally characterize the creation of the IBES as an example of "incremental change" rather than comprehensive reform.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Civil society organizations, such as Transparency International, have criticized the final agreement as "toothless" due to its inability to independently investigate or sanction the EU institutions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Similarly, legal scholars point out that the body lacks investigative powers and the capacity to apply ethical standards to concrete individual cases.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Nevertheless, because the body requires each participating institution to conduct a public, written self-assessment of its internal rules, experts suggest that the ensuing public scrutiny and institutional peer pressure may induce institutions to align their standards more closely over time.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union had an agreed budget of €170.6 billion in 2022.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU had a long-term budget of €1,082.5 billion for the period 2014–2020, representing 1.02% of the EU-28's GNI.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 1960, the budget of the European Community was 0.03 per cent of GDP.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Of this, €54bn subsidised agriculture enterprise, €42bn was spent on transport, building and the environment, €16bn on education and research, €13bn on welfare, €20bn on foreign and defence policy, €2bn in finance, €2bn in energy, €1.5bn in communications, and €13bn in administration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In November 2020, two members of the union, Hungary and Poland, blocked approval to the EU's budget at a meeting in the Committee of Permanent Representatives (Coreper), citing a proposal that linked funding with adherence to the rule of law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The budget included a COVID-19 recovery fund of €750 billion.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The budget was finally approved by 12 December when Hungary and Poland withdrew their vetoes after further negotiations in the council and the European Council.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Bodies combatting fraud have also been established, including the European Anti-fraud Office and the European Public Prosecutor's Office.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The latter is a decentralised independent body of the European Union (EU), established under the Treaty of Lisbon between 22 of the 27 states of the EU following the method of enhanced cooperation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Public Prosecutor's Office investigate and prosecute fraud against the budget of the European Union and other crimes against the EU's financial interests including fraud concerning EU funds of over €10,000 and cross-border VAT fraud cases involving damages above €10 million.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Constitutionally, the EU bears some resemblance to both a confederation and a federation, but has not formally defined itself as either.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] (It does not have a formal constitution: its status is defined by the Treaty of European Union and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It is more integrated than a traditional confederation of states because the general level of government widely employs qualified majority voting in some decision-making among the member states, rather than relying exclusively on unanimity.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU is less integrated than a federal state because it is not a state in its own right: sovereignty continues to flow 'from the bottom up', from the several peoples of the separate member states, rather than from a single undifferentiated whole.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In addition, the principle of subsidiarity requires that only those matters that need to be determined collectively are so determined.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Under the principle of supremacy, national courts are required to enforce the treaties that their member states have ratified, even if doing so requires them to ignore conflicting national law, and (within limits) even constitutional provisions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The direct effect and supremacy doctrines were not explicitly set out in the European Treaties but were developed by the Court of Justice itself over the 1960s, apparently under the influence of its then most influential judge, Frenchman Robert Lecourt.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The question whether the secondary law enacted by the EU has a comparable status in relation to national legislation, has been a matter of debate among legal scholars.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union is based on a series of treaties.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] These first established the European Community and the EU, and then made amendments to those founding treaties.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] These are power-giving treaties which set broad policy goals and establish institutions with the necessary legal powers to implement those goals.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] These legal powers include the ability to enact legislation which can directly affect all member states and their inhabitants.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU has legal personality, with the right to sign agreements and international treaties.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The main legal acts of the European Union come in three forms: regulations, directives, and decisions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Regulations become law in all member states the moment they come into force, without the requirement for any implementing measures, and automatically override conflicting domestic provisions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Directives require member states to achieve a certain result while leaving them discretion as to how to achieve the result.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The details of how they are to be implemented are left to member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] When the time limit for implementing directives passes, they may, under certain conditions, have direct effect in national law against member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Decisions offer an alternative to the two above modes of legislation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] They are legal acts which only apply to specified individuals, companies or a particular member state.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] They are most often used in competition law, or on rulings on State Aid, but are also frequently used for procedural or administrative matters within the institutions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Regulations, directives, and decisions are of equal legal value and apply without any formal hierarchy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Foreign policy co-operation between member states dates from the establishment of the community in 1957, when member states negotiated as a bloc in international trade negotiations under the EU's common commercial policy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Steps for more wide-ranging co-ordination in foreign relations began in 1970 with the establishment of European Political Cooperation which created an informal consultation process between member states with the aim of forming common foreign policies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 1987 the European Political Cooperation was introduced on a formal basis by the Single European Act.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EPC was renamed as the Common Foreign and Security Policy (CFSP) by the Maastricht Treaty.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The stated aims of the CFSP are to promote both the EU's own interests and those of the international community as a whole, including the furtherance of international co-operation, respect for human rights, democracy, and the rule of law.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The CFSP requires unanimity among the member states on the appropriate policy to follow on any particular issue.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The unanimity and difficult issues treated under the CFSP sometimes lead to disagreements, such as those which occurred over the war in Iraq.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The high representative heads up the European External Action Service (EEAS), a unique EU department that has been officially implemented and operational since 1 December 2010 on the occasion of the first anniversary of the entry into force of the Treaty of Lisbon.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EEAS serves as a foreign ministry and diplomatic corps for the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Besides the emerging international policy of the European Union, the international influence of the EU is also felt through enlargement.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The perceived benefits of becoming a member of the EU act as an incentive for both political and economic reform in states wishing to fulfil the EU's accession criteria, and are considered an important factor contributing to the reform of European formerly Communist countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] This influence on the internal affairs of other countries is generally referred to as "soft power", as opposed to military "hard power".
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Commission's Humanitarian Aid and Civil Protection department, or "ECHO", provides humanitarian aid from the EU to developing countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 2012, its budget amounted to €874 million, 51 per cent of the budget went to Africa and 20 per cent to Asia, Latin America, the Caribbean and Pacific, and 20 per cent to the Middle East and Mediterranean.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Humanitarian aid is financed directly by the budget (70 per cent) as part of the financial instruments for external action and also by the European Development Fund (30 per cent).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU's external action financing is divided into geographic instruments and thematic instruments.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 2016, the average among EU countries was 0.4 per cent and five had met or exceeded the 0.7 per cent target: Denmark, Germany, Luxembourg, Sweden, and the United Kingdom.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union uses foreign relations instruments like the European Neighbourhood Policy which seeks to tie those countries to the east and south of the European territory of the EU to the union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] These countries, primarily developing countries, include some who seek to one day become either a member state of the European Union, or more closely integrated with the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU offers financial assistance to countries within the European Neighbourhood, so long as they meet the strict conditions of government reform, economic reform and other issues surrounding positive transformation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] This process is normally underpinned by an Action Plan, as agreed by both Brussels and the target country.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] There is also the worldwide European Union Global Strategy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] International recognition of sustainable development as a key element is growing steadily.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Other key global agreements are the Paris Agreement and the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (United Nations, 2015).
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The SDGs recognise that all countries must stimulate action in the following key areas – people, planet, prosperity, peace and partnership – in order to tackle the global challenges that are crucial for the survival of humanity.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EU development action is based on the European Consensus on Development, which was endorsed on 20 December 2005 by EU Member States, the council, the European Parliament and the commission.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] It is applied from the principles of capability approach and rights-based approach to development.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Funding is provided by the Instrument for Pre-Accession Assistance and the Global Europe programmes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Partnership and cooperation agreements are bilateral agreements with non-member nations.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The predecessors of the European Union were not devised as a military alliance because NATO was largely seen as appropriate and sufficient for defence purposes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Twenty-three EU members are members of NATO while the remaining member states follow policies of neutrality.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Western European Union, a military alliance with a mutual defence clause, closed in 2011 as its role had been transferred to the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] To that end, a number of efforts were made to increase the EU's military capability, notably the Helsinki Headline Goal process.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] After much discussion, the most concrete result was the EU Battlegroups initiative, each of which is planned to be able to deploy quickly about 1500 personnel.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Since the withdrawal of the United Kingdom, France is the only member officially recognised as a nuclear weapon state and the sole holder of a permanent seat on the United Nations Security Council.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] France and Italy are also the only EU countries that have power projection capabilities outside of Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Italy, Germany, the Netherlands and Belgium participate in NATO nuclear sharing.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Most EU member states opposed the Nuclear Weapon Ban Treaty.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EU forces have been deployed on peacekeeping missions from middle and northern Africa to the western Balkans and western Asia.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EU military operations are supported by a number of bodies, including the European Defence Agency, European Union Satellite Centre and the European Union Military Staff.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union Military Staff is under the authority of the High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy and the Political and Security Committee.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In an EU consisting of 27 members, substantial security and defence co-operation is increasingly relying on collaboration among all member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Border and Coast Guard Agency (Frontex) is an agency of the EU aiming to detect and stop illegal immigration, human trafficking and terrorist infiltration.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU also operates the European Travel Information and Authorisation System, the Entry/Exit System, the Schengen Information System, the Visa Information System and the Common European Asylum System which provide common databases for police and immigration authorities.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The impetus for the development of this co-operation was the advent of open borders in the Schengen Area and the associated cross-border crime.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU's member states cover an area of 4,233,262 square kilometres (1,634,472 sq mi), and therefore a large part of the European continent.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU's highest peak is Mont Blanc in the Graian Alps, 4,810.45 metres (15,782 ft) above sea level.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The lowest points in the EU are Lammefjorden, Denmark, and Zuidplaspolder, Netherlands, at 7 m (23 ft) below sea level.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The landscape, climate, and economy of the EU are influenced by its coastline, which is 65,993 kilometres (41,006 mi) long.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In addition to national territories in Europe, there are 32 special territories of members of the European Economic Area, not all of which are part of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The largest by area is Greenland, which is not part of the EU but whose citizens are EU citizens, while the largest by population are the Canary Islands off Africa, which are part of the EU and the Schengen area.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] French Guiana in South America is part of the EU and the eurozone, as is Mayotte, north of Madagascar.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The climate of the European Union is of a temperate, continental nature, with a maritime climate prevailing on the western coasts and a mediterranean climate in the south.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The climate is strongly conditioned by the Gulf Stream, which warms the western region to levels unattainable at similar latitudes on other continents.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Western Europe is oceanic, while eastern Europe is continental and dry.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Four seasons occur in western Europe, while southern Europe experiences a wet season and a dry season.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Southern Europe is hot and dry during the summer months.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The heaviest precipitation occurs downwind of water bodies due to the prevailing westerlies, with higher amounts also seen in the Alps.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 1957, when the European Economic Community was founded, it had no environmental policy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Over the past 50 years, an increasingly dense network of legislation has been created, extending to all areas of environmental protection, including air pollution, water quality, waste management, nature conservation, and the control of chemicals, industrial hazards, and biotechnology.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] According to the Institute for European Environmental Policy, environmental law comprises over 500 Directives, Regulations and Decisions, making environmental policy a core area of European politics.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] European policy-makers originally increased the EU's capacity to act on environmental issues by defining it as a trade problem.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Trade barriers and competitive distortions in the Common Market could emerge due to the different environmental standards in each member state.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In subsequent years, the environment became a formal policy area, with its own policy actors, principles and procedures.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The legal basis for EU environmental policy was established with the introduction of the Single European Act in 1987.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Initially, EU environmental policy focused on Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] More recently, the EU has demonstrated leadership in global environmental governance, e.g. the role of the EU in securing the ratification and coming into force of the Kyoto Protocol despite opposition from the United States.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] This international dimension is reflected in the EU's Sixth Environmental Action Programme, which recognises that its objectives can only be achieved if key international agreements are actively supported and properly implemented both at EU level and worldwide.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Lisbon Treaty further strengthened the leadership ambitions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] EU law has played a significant role in improving habitat and species protection in Europe, as well as contributing to improvements in air and water quality and waste management.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Mitigating climate change is one of the top priorities of EU environmental policy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 2007, member states agreed that, in the future, 20 per cent of the energy used across the EU must be renewable, and carbon dioxide emissions have to be lower in 2020 by at least 20 per cent compared to 1990 levels.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 2017, the EU emitted 9.1 per cent of global greenhouse-gas emissions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Union claims that already in 2018, its GHG emissions were 23% lower than in 1990.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The EU has adopted an emissions trading system to incorporate carbon emissions into the economy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The European Green Capital is an annual award given to cities that focuses on the environment, energy efficiency, and quality of life in urban areas to create smart city.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In the 2019 elections to the European Parliament, the green parties increased their power, possibly because of the rise of post materialist values.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Proposals to reach a zero carbon economy in the European Union by 2050 were suggested in 2018–2019.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Almost all member states supported that goal at an EU summit in June 2019.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, and Poland disagreed.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In June 2021, the European Union passed a European Climate Law with targets of 55% GHG emissions reduction by 2030 and carbon neutrality by 2050.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] Also in the same year, the European Union and the United States pledged to cut methane emissions by 30% by 2030.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] The pledge is considered as a big achievement for climate change mitigation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] A research report from November 2024 declared that the Czech Republic is the EU's most toxic country in Europe for car emissions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] In 2025, The European Union together with China, Brazil and others, joined the Global carbon market coalition.
[src:european-union/european-union-p02] According to some calculations, a global carbon market can speed up emission reduction seven-fold.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The gross domestic product (GDP), a measure of economic activity, of EU member states was US$16.64 trillion in 2022, around 16.6 per cent of the world GDP.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There is a significant variation in GDP per capita between and within individual EU states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The difference between the richest and poorest regions (281 NUTS-2 regions of the Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics) ranged, in 2017, from 31 per cent (Severozapaden, Bulgaria) of the EU28 average (€30,000) to 253 per cent (Luxembourg), or from €4,600 to €92,600.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] EU member states own the estimated third largest after the United States (US$140 trillion) and China (US$84 trillion) net wealth in the world, equal to around one sixth (US$76 trillion) of the US$454 trillion global wealth.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Of the top 500 largest corporations in the world measured by revenue in 2024, 90 had their headquarters in the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2016, unemployment in the EU stood at 8.9 per cent while inflation was at 2.2 per cent, and the account balance at −0.9 per cent of GDP.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The average annual net earnings in the European Union was around €25,000 in 2021.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The euro is the official currency in 21 member states of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The creation of a European single currency became an official objective of the European Economic Community in 1969.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 1992, having negotiated the structure and procedures of a currency union, the member states signed the Maastricht Treaty and were legally bound to fulfil the agreed-on rules including the convergence criteria if they wanted to join the monetary union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The states wanting to participate had first to join the European Exchange Rate Mechanism.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Free movement of capital is intended to permit movement of investments such as property purchases and buying of shares between countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Until the drive towards economic and monetary union the development of the capital provisions had been slow.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Post-Maastricht there has been a rapidly developing corpus of ECJ judgements regarding this initially neglected freedom.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The free movement of capital is unique insofar as it is granted equally to non-member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European System of Financial Supervision is an institutional architecture of the EU's framework of financial supervision composed by three authorities: the European Banking Authority, the European Insurance and Occupational Pensions Authority and the European Securities and Markets Authority.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] To complement this framework, there is also a European Systemic Risk Board under the responsibility of the central bank.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The aim of this financial control system is to ensure the economic stability of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 1999, the currency union started to materialise through introducing a common accounting (virtual) currency in eleven of the member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2002, it was turned into a fully-fledged conventible currency, when euro notes and coins were issued, while the phaseout of national currencies in the eurozone (consisting by then of 12 member states) was initiated.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The eurozone (constituted by the EU member states which have adopted the euro) has since grown to 20 countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The 20 EU member states known collectively as the eurozone have fully implemented the currency union by superseding their national currencies with the euro.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The currency union represents 345 million EU citizens.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The euro is the second largest reserve currency as well as the second most traded currency in the world after the United States dollar.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The euro, and the monetary policies of those who have adopted it in agreement with the EU, are under the control of the ECB.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The ECB is the central bank for the eurozone, and thus controls monetary policy in that area with an agenda to maintain price stability.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It is at the centre of the Eurosystem, which comprehends all the eurozone national central banks.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The ECB is also the central institution of the Banking Union established within the eurozone, as the hub of European Banking Supervision.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There is also a Single Resolution Mechanism in case of a bank default.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] As a political entity, the European Union is represented in the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Two of the original core objectives of the European Economic Community were the development of a common market, subsequently becoming a single market, and a customs union between its member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The single market involves the free circulation of goods, capital, people, and services within the EU, The free movement of services and of establishment allows self-employed persons to move between member states to provide services on a temporary or permanent basis.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] While services account for 60 per cent to 70 per cent of GDP, legislation in the area is not as developed as in other areas.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This lacuna has been addressed by the Services in the Internal Market Directive 2006 which aims to liberalise the cross border provision of services.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] According to the treaty the provision of services is a residual freedom that only applies if no other freedom is being exercised.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The customs union involves the application of a common external tariff on all goods entering the market.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Once goods have been admitted into the market they cannot be subjected to customs duties, discriminatory taxes or import quotas, as they travel internally.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The non-EU member states of Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland participate in the single market but not in the customs union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Half the trade in the EU is covered by legislation harmonised by the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union Association Agreement does something similar for a much larger range of countries, partly as a so-called soft approach ('a carrot instead of a stick') to influence the politics in those countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union represents all its members at the World Trade Organization (WTO), and acts on behalf of member states in any disputes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] When the EU negotiates trade related agreement outside the WTO framework, the subsequent agreement must be approved by each individual EU member state government.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU operates a competition policy intended to ensure undistorted competition within the single market.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2001 the commission for the first time prevented a merger between two companies based in the United States (General Electric and Honeywell) which had already been approved by their national authority.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Another high-profile case, against Microsoft, resulted in the commission fining Microsoft over €777 million following nine years of legal action.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union has concluded free trade agreements (FTAs) and other agreements with a trade component with many countries worldwide and is negotiating with many others.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union's services trade surplus rose from $16 billion in 2000 to more than $250 billion in 2018.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2020, in part due to the COVID-19 pandemic, China became the EU's largest trading partner, displacing the United States.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union is the largest exporter in the world and in 2008 was the largest importer of goods and services.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Internal trade between the member states is aided by the removal of barriers to trade such as tariffs and border controls.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In the eurozone, trade is helped by not having any currency differences to deal with amongst most members.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Externally, the EU's free-trade agreement with Japan is perhaps its most notable one.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU-Japan Economic Partnership Agreement was officially signed on 17 July 2018, becoming the world's largest bilateral free trade deal when it went into effect on 1 February 2019, creating an open trade zone covering nearly one-third of global GDP.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The total energy supply of the EU was 59 billion GJ in 2019, about 10.2 per cent of the world total.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Approximately three fifths of the energy available in the EU came from imports (mostly of fossil fuels).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Renewable energy contributed 18.1 per cent of the EU's total energy supply in 2019, and 11.1 per cent of the final energy consumption.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU has had legislative power in the area of energy policy for most of its existence; this has its roots in the original European Coal and Steel Community.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The introduction of a mandatory and comprehensive European energy policy was approved at the meeting of the European Council in October 2005, and the first draft policy was published in January 2007.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2007, EU countries as a whole imported 82 per cent of their oil, 57 per cent of their natural gas and 97.48 per cent of their uranium demands.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The three largest suppliers of natural gas to the European Union are Russia, Norway and Algeria, that amounted for about three quarters of the imports in 2019.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There is a strong dependence on Russian energy that the EU has been attempting to reduce.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In May 2022, it was reported that the European Union was preparing another sanction against Russia over its invasion of Ukraine.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It is expected to target Russian oil, Russian and Belarusian banks, as well as individuals and companies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] According to an article by Reuters, two diplomats stated that the European Union may impose a ban on imports of Russian oil by the end of 2022.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Also in May 2022, the European Commission published the RePowerEU initiative, a €300 billion plan outlining the path towards the end of EU dependence on Russian fossil fuels by 2030 and the acceleration on the clean energy transition.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union manages cross-border road, railway, airport and water infrastructure through the Trans-European Transport Network (TEN-T), created in 1990, and the Trans-European Combined Transport network.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] TEN-T comprises two network layers: the Core Network, which is to be completed by 2030; and the Comprehensive Network, which is to be completed by 2050.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Road transportation was organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European road network.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Bundesautobahn 7 is the longest national motorway in the EU at 963 km (598 mi).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Maritime transportation is organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European Inland Waterway network, and the Trans-European Seaport network.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] European seaports are categorised as international, community, or regional.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Port of Rotterdam is the busiest in the EU, and the world's largest seaport outside of East Asia, located in and near the city of Rotterdam, in the province of South Holland in the Netherlands.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Maritime Safety Agency (EMSA), founded in 2002 in Lisbon, Portugal, is charged with reducing the risk of maritime accidents, marine pollution from ships and the loss of human lives at sea by helping to enforce the pertinent EU legislation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Air transportation is organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European Airport network.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] European airports are categorised as international, community, or regional.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Charles de Gaulle Airport is the busiest in the EU, located in and near the city of Paris, in France.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Common Aviation Area (ECAA) is a single market in aviation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] ECAA agreements were signed on 5 May 2006 in Salzburg, Austria between the EU and some third countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The ECAA liberalises the air transport industry by allowing any company from any ECAA member state to fly between any ECAA member states airports, thereby allowing a "foreign" airline to provide domestic flights.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Civil aviation safety is under the responsibility of the European Union Aviation Safety Agency (EASA).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It carries out certification, regulation and standardisation and also performs investigation and monitoring.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The idea of a European-level aviation safety authority goes back to 1996, but the agency was only legally established in 2002, and began operating in 2003.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Rail transportation is organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European Rail network, made up of the high-speed rail network and the conventional rail network.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Gare du Nord railway station is the busiest in the EU, located in and near the city of Paris, in France.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Rail transport in Europe is being synchronised with the European Rail Traffic Management System (ERTMS) with the goal of greatly enhancing safety, increase efficiency of train transports and enhance cross-border interoperability.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This is done by replacing former national signalling equipment and operational procedures with a single new Europe-wide standard for train control and command systems.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This system is conducted by the European Union Agency for Railways (ERA).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Schengen Area is an area comprising 29 European countries that have officially abolished all passport and all other types of border control at their mutual borders.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Being an element within the wider area of freedom, security and justice policy of the EU, it mostly functions as a single jurisdiction under a common visa policy for international travel purposes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The area is named after the 1985 Schengen Agreement and the 1990 Schengen Convention, both signed in Schengen, Luxembourg.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Of the 27 EU member states, 25 participate in the Schengen Area.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Of the EU members that are not part of the Schengen Area, one—Cyprus—is legally obligated to join the area in the future; Ireland maintains an opt-out, and instead operates its own visa policy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The four European Free Trade Association (EFTA) member states, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, and Switzerland, are not members of the EU, but have signed agreements in association with the Schengen Agreement.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Mobile communication roaming charges are abolished throughout the EU, Iceland, Liechtenstein and Norway.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This was the first common political framework for space activities established by the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Each member state has pursued to some extent their own national space policy, though often co-ordinating through the ESA.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Galileo is a global navigation satellite system (GNSS) that went live in 2016, created by the EU through the ESA, operated by the EUSPA, with two ground operations centres in Fucino, Italy, and Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The €10 billion project is named after the Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] One of the aims of Galileo is to provide an independent high-precision positioning system so European political and military authorities do not have to rely on the US GPS, or the Russian GLONASS systems, which could be disabled or degraded by their operators at any time.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Geostationary Navigation Overlay Service (EGNOS) is a satellite-based augmentation system (SBAS) developed by the ESA and EUROCONTROL.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Currently, it supplements the GPS by reporting on the reliability and accuracy of their positioning data and sending out corrections.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The system will supplement Galileo in a future version.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Copernicus Programme is the EU's Earth observation programme coordinated and managed by EUSPA in partnership with ESA.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) is the agricultural policy of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It implements a system of agricultural subsidies and other programmes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It was introduced in 1962 and has since then undergone several changes to reduce the EEC budget cost (from 73% in 1985 to 37% in 2017) and consider rural development in its aims.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It has, however, been criticised on the grounds of its cost and its environmental and humanitarian effects.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Likewise, the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) is the fisheries policy of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It sets quotas for which member states are allowed to catch each type of fish, as well as encouraging the fishing industry by various market interventions and fishing subsidies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It was introduced in 2009 with the Treaty of Lisbon, which formally enshrined fisheries conservation policy as one of the handful of "exclusive competences" reserved for the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The free movement of persons means that EU citizens can move freely between member states to live, work, study or retire in another country.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This required the lowering of administrative formalities and recognition of professional qualifications of other states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 6.7 per cent in September 2018.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The euro area unemployment rate was 8.1 per cent.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Among the member states, the lowest unemployment rates were recorded in the Czech Republic (2.3 per cent), Germany and Poland (both 3.4 per cent), and the highest in Spain (10.61 per cent in 2024) and Greece (9.6 per cent in November 2024).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union has long sought to mitigate the effects of free markets by protecting workers' rights and preventing social and environmental dumping.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] To this end, it has adopted laws establishing minimum employment and environmental standards.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] These included the Working Time Directive and the Environmental Impact Assessment Directive.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Directive about Minimum Wage, which looks to lift minimum wages and strengthen collective bargaining was approved by the European Parliament in September 2022.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The five European Structural and Investment Funds are supporting the development of the EU regions, primarily the underdeveloped ones, located mostly in the states of central and southern Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Another fund (the Instrument for Pre-Accession Assistance) provides support for candidate members to transform their country to conform to the EU's standard.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Demographic transition to a society of ageing population, low fertility-rates and depopulation of non-metropolitan regions is tackled within this policies.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The population of the EU in 2024 was about 450 million people, corresponding to 5.8 per cent of the world population.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The population density across the EU was 106 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is more than the world average.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It is highest in areas in central and western Europe, sometimes referred to as the "blue banana", while Sweden and Finland in the north are much more sparsely populated.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The total population of the EU has been slightly decreasing for several years, contracting by 0.04 per cent in 2021.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This is due to a low birth rate of about 1.5 children per woman, less than the world average of 2.3.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In total, 4.1 million babies were born in the EU in 2021.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Of the people residing in the EU, 5.3 per cent are not EU citizens.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There were 31 non-EU citizenships that each accounted for at least 1 per cent of non-EU citizens living in the EU, of which the largest were Moroccan, Turkish, Syrian and Chinese.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Around 1.9 million people immigrated to one of the EU member states from a non-EU country during 2020, and a total of 956,000 people emigrated from a member state to go to a non-EU country during the same year.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] More than two thirds (68.2%) of EU inhabitants lived in urban areas in 2020, which is slightly less than the world average.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Cities are largely spread out across the EU with a large grouping in and around the Benelux.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU contains about 40 urban areas with populations of over 1 million.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] With a population of over 13 million, Paris is the largest metropolitan area and the only megacity in the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Paris is followed by Madrid, Barcelona, Berlin, the Ruhr, Milan, and Rome, all with a metropolitan population of over 4 million.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU has 24 official languages: Bulgarian, Croatian, Czech, Danish, Dutch, English, Estonian, Finnish, French, German, Greek, Hungarian, Italian, Irish, Latvian, Lithuanian, Maltese, Polish, Portuguese, Romanian, Slovak, Slovene, Spanish, and Swedish.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Important documents, such as legislation, are translated into every official language and the European Parliament provides translation for documents and plenary sessions.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Even though language policy is the responsibility of member states, EU institutions promote multilingualism among its citizens.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The most widely spoken language in the EU is English; the language is spoken by 50 per cent of the population and studied by 95 per cent of school students, although following the withdrawal of the United Kingdom only 2% of the population speak it natively.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] German and French are spoken by 29 per cent and 25 per cent of the population.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] More than half (59 per cent) of EU citizens are able to engage in a conversation in a language other than their mother tongue, and more than a tenth (11%) are quadrilingual.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Luxembourgish (in Luxembourg) and Turkish (in Cyprus) are the only two national languages that are not official languages of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Catalan, Galician and Basque are not recognised official languages of the EU but have official status in Spain.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Therefore, official translations of the treaties are made into them and citizens have the right to correspond with the institutions in these languages.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There are about 150 regional and minority languages in the EU, spoken by up to 50 million people.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages ratified by most EU states provides general guidelines that states can follow to protect their linguistic heritage.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Day of Languages is held annually on 26 September and is aimed at encouraging language learning across Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU has no formal connection to any religion.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Article 17 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union recognises the "status under national law of churches and religious associations" as well as that of "philosophical and non-confessional organisations".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The preamble to the Treaty on European Union mentions the "cultural, religious and humanist inheritance of Europe".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Discussion over the draft texts of the European Constitution and later the Treaty of Lisbon included proposals to mention Christianity or a god, or both, in the preamble of the text, but the idea faced opposition and was dropped.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Christians in the EU include Catholics of both Latin and Eastern Rite, numerous Protestant denominations with Lutherans, Anglicans, and Reformed forming the majority of Protestant affiliations, and the Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2009, the EU had an estimated Muslim population of 13 million, and an estimated Jewish population of over a million.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The other world religions of Buddhism, Hinduism, and Sikhism are also represented in the EU population.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Eurostat's Eurobarometer opinion polls showed in 2005 that 52 per cent of EU citizens believed in a god, 27 per cent in "some sort of spirit or life force", and 18 per cent had no form of belief.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Into the 21st century, many countries have experienced falling church attendance and membership.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The countries where the fewest people reported a religious belief were Estonia (16 per cent) and the Czech Republic (19 per cent).
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The most religious countries were Malta (95 per cent, predominantly Catholic) as well as Cyprus and Romania (both predominantly Orthodox) each with about 90 per cent of citizens professing a belief in God.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Across the EU, belief was higher among women, older people, those with religious upbringing, those who left school at 15 or 16, and those "positioning themselves on the right of the political scale".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Basic education is an area where the EU's role is limited to supporting national governments.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In higher education, the policy was developed in the 1980s in programmes supporting exchanges and mobility.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The most visible of these has been the Erasmus Programme, a university exchange programme which began in 1987.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In its first 20 years, it supported international exchange opportunities for well over 1.5 million university and college students and became a symbol of European student life.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There are similar programmes for school pupils and teachers, for trainees in vocational education and training, and for adult learners in the Lifelong Learning Programme 2007–2013.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] These programmes are designed to encourage a wider knowledge of other countries and to spread good practices in the education and training fields across the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Through its support of the Bologna Process, the EU is supporting comparable standards and compatible degrees across Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Scientific development is facilitated through the EU's Framework Programmes, the first of which started in 1984.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The aims of EU policy in this area are to co-ordinate and stimulate research.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The independent European Research Council allocates EU funds to European or national research projects.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] EU research and technological framework programmes deal in a number of areas, for example energy where the aim is to develop a diverse mix of renewable energy to help the environment and to reduce dependence on imported fuels.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Article 35 of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union affirms that "A high level of human health protection shall be ensured in the definition and implementation of all Union policies and activities".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Commission's Directorate-General for Health and Consumers seeks to align national laws on the protection of people's health, on the consumers' rights, on the safety of food and other products.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] All EU and many other European countries offer their citizens a free European Health Insurance Card which, on a reciprocal basis, provides insurance for emergency medical treatment insurance when visiting other participating European countries.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] A directive on cross-border healthcare aims at promoting co-operation on health care between member states and facilitating access to safe and high-quality cross-border healthcare for European patients.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The life expectancy in the EU was 80.1 year at birth in 2021, among the highest in the world and around nine years higher than the world average.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In general, life expectancy is lower in Eastern Europe than in Western Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2018, the EU region with the highest life expectancy was Madrid, Spain at 85.2 years, followed by the Spanish regions of La Rioja and Castilla y León both at 84.3 years, Trentino in Italy at 84.3 years and Île-de-France in France at 84.2 years.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU has also sought to coordinate the social security and health systems of member states to facilitate individuals exercising free movement rights and to ensure they maintain their ability to access social security and health services in other member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Since 2019 there has been a European commissioner for equality and the European Institute for Gender Equality has existed since 2007.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] A Directive on countering gender-based violence has been proposed.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In September 2022, a European Care strategy was approved in order to provide "quality, affordable and accessible care services".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Social Charter is the main body that recognises the social rights of European citizens.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2020, the first ever European Union Strategy on LGBTIQ equality was approved under Helena Dalli mandate.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In December 2021, the commission announced the intention of codifying a union-wide law against LGBT hate crimes.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Since the creation of the European Union in 1993, it has developed its competencies in the area of justice and home affairs; initially at an intergovernmental level and later by supranationalism.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Accordingly, the union has legislated in areas such as extradition, family law, asylum law, and criminal justice.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU has also established agencies to co-ordinate police, prosecution and civil litigations across the member states: Europol for police co-operation, CEPOL for training of police forces and the Eurojust for co-operation between prosecutors and courts.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It also operates the EUCARIS database of vehicles and drivers, the Eurodac, the European Criminal Records Information System, the European Cybercrime Centre, FADO, PRADO and others.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Prohibitions against discrimination have a long standing in the treaties.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In more recent years, these have been supplemented by powers to legislate against discrimination based on race, religion, disability, age, and sexual orientation.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] In 2009, the Lisbon Treaty gave legal effect to the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The charter is a codified catalogue of fundamental rights against which the EU's legal acts can be judged.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It consolidates many rights which were previously recognised by the Court of Justice and derived from the "constitutional traditions common to the member states".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Court of Justice has long recognised fundamental rights and has, on occasion, invalidated EU legislation based on its failure to adhere to those fundamental rights.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Signing the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) is a condition for EU membership.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Previously, the EU itself could not accede to the convention as it is neither a state nor had the competence to accede.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Lisbon Treaty and Protocol 14 to the ECHR have changed this: the former binds the EU to accede to the convention while the latter formally permits it.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU is independent from the Council of Europe, although they share purpose and ideas, especially on the rule of law, human rights and democracy.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Furthermore, the European Convention on Human Rights and European Social Charter, as well as the source of law for the Charter of Fundamental Rights are created by the Council of Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU has also promoted human rights issues in the wider world.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU opposes the death penalty and has proposed its worldwide abolition.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Abolition of the death penalty is a condition for EU membership.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] On 19 October 2020, the European Union revealed new plans to create a legal structure to act against human rights violations worldwide.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The new plan was expected to provide the European Union with greater flexibility to target and sanction those responsible for serious human rights violations and abuses around the world.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Cultural co-operation between member states has been an interest of the European Union since its inclusion as a community competency in the Maastricht Treaty.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Actions taken in the cultural area by the EU include the Culture 2000 seven-year programme, the European Cultural Month event, and orchestras such as the European Union Youth Orchestra.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Capital of Culture programme selects one or more cities in every year to assist the cultural development of that city.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Sport is mainly the responsibility of the member states or other international organisations, rather than of the EU.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] There are some EU policies that have affected sport, such as the free movement of workers, which was at the core of the Bosman ruling that prohibited national football leagues from imposing quotas on foreign players with EU member state citizenship.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Treaty of Lisbon requires any application of economic rules to take into account the specific nature of sport and its structures based on voluntary activity.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] This followed lobbying by governing organisations such as the International Olympic Committee and FIFA, due to objections over the application of free market principles to sport, which led to an increasing gap between rich and poor clubs.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The EU does fund a programme for Israeli, Jordanian, Irish, and British football coaches, as part of the Football 4 Peace project.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The flag of Europe consists of a circle of 12 golden stars on a blue background.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Originally designed in 1955 for the Council of Europe, the flag was adopted by the European Communities, the predecessors of the present European Union, in 1986.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The Council of Europe gave the flag a symbolic description in the following terms, although the official symbolic description adopted by the EU omits the reference to the "Western world".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Charles the Great, also known as Charlemagne (Latin: *Carolus Magnus*) and later recognised as *Pater Europae* ("Father of Europe"), has a symbolic relevance to Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The commission has named one of its central buildings in Brussels after Charlemagne and the city of Aachen has since 1949 awarded the Charlemagne Prize to champions of European unification.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Since 2008, the organisers of this prize, in conjunction with the European Parliament, have awarded the Charlemagne Youth Prize in recognition of similar efforts led by young people.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Media freedom is a fundamental right that applies to all member states of the European Union and its citizens, as defined in the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights as well as the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Within the EU enlargement process, guaranteeing media freedom is named a "key indicator of a country's readiness to become part of the EU".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The majority of media in the European Union are national-orientated, although some EU-wide media focusing on European affairs have emerged since the early 1990s, such as Euronews, Eurosport, EUobserver, EURACTIV or Politico Europe.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Arte is a public Franco-German TV network that promotes programming in the areas of culture and the arts.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] 80 per cent of its programming are provided in equal proportion by the two member companies, while the remainder is being provided by the European Economic Interest Grouping *ARTE GEIE* and the channel's European partners.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The MEDIA Programme of the European Union has supported the European popular film and audiovisual industries since 1991.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] It provides support for the development, promotion and distribution of European works within Europe and beyond.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union has had a significant positive economic effect on most member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] According to a 2019 study of the member states who joined from 1973 to 2004, "without European integration, per capita incomes would have been, on average, approximately 10% lower in the first ten years after joining the EU".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Greece was the exception reported by the study, which analysed up to 2008, "to avoid confounding effects from the global financial crisis".
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] A 2021 study in the *Journal of Political Economy* found that the 2004 enlargement had aggregate beneficial economic effects on all groups in both the old and new member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The largest winners were the new member states, in particular unskilled labour in the new member states.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] The European Union is frequently cited as having made a major contribution to peace in Europe, in particular by pacifying border disputes, and to the spread of democracy, especially by encouraging democratic reforms in aspiring Eastern European member states after the collapse of the USSR.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] Scholar Thomas Risse wrote in 2009, "there is a consensus in the literature on Eastern Europe that the EU membership perspective had a huge anchoring effects for the new democracies." However, R.
[src:european-union/european-union-p03] At the same time, the union might provide through Article 7 of the Treaty on European Union an external constraint that prevents electoral autocracies, currently Hungary, from progressing into closed autocracies.
